{"title_page": "Rogers Communications", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian telecommunications company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name          = Rogers Communications Inc.\n| logo          = Rogers logo.svg\n| logo_caption  = Rogers logo, used since 2015\n| image         = Rogers AT&T Centre.JPG\n| image_size    = 220px\n| image_caption = The [[Rogers Building (Toronto)|Rogers Building]] in Toronto, Ontario\n| type          = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as     = {{TSX|RCI.A|RCI.B}}<br />[[S&P/TSX 60|S&P/TSX 60 component]]\n| founder       = [[Edward S. Rogers Jr.|Ted Rogers]]\n| key_people    = [[Edward S. Rogers III]] {{small|(Chairman)}}<ref name=Directors/><br />Joe Natale {{small|(President & CEO)}}\n| industry      = [[Telecommunications]]<br/>[[Mass media]]\n| products      = [[Landline]] and [[mobile phone|mobile]] telephony, [[Internet]] services, [[digital television]], [[broadcasting]], [[cable TV]], [[publishing]]\n| revenue       = [[Canadian dollar|C$]]14.143 billion (2017)<ref name=\"rogers.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rogers.com/web/ir/financial-reporting/financial-historyf|title=Rogers Investor Relations|website=Rogers Investor Relations|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref>\n| net_income    = C$1.821 billion (2017)<ref name=\"rogers.com\"/>\n| assets        = C$29.175 billion (2015)<ref name=\"rogers.com\"/>\n| equity        = C$5.745 billion (2015)\n| num_employees = 26,000 (2013)<ref name=\"rogers.com\"/>\n| subsid        = {{ubl|[[Fido Solutions]]|[[Chatr]]|[[Rogers Communications#Rogers Bank|Rogers Bank]]|[[Rogers Cable]]|[[Rogers Media]]|[[Rogers Telecom]]|[[Rogers Wireless]]}}\n| homepage      = {{URL|https://www.rogers.com/}}\n| foundation    = 1960<ref>[http://about.rogers.com/About/Our_History.aspx About Rogers: Our History] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004095504/http://about.rogers.com/About/Our_History.aspx |date=2013-10-04 }}, rogers.com.</ref>\n| location      = 333 [[Bloor Street]] East<br />[[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]<br />M4W 1G9\n}}\n\n'''Rogers Communications Inc.''' is a Canadian communications and media company. It operates primarily in the fields of [[mobile phone operator|wireless communications]], [[cable television]], [[telephony]] and [[Internet access|Internet connectivity]], with significant additional [[telecommunications]] and [[mass media]] assets. Rogers has its headquarters in [[Toronto]], Ontario.<ref>\"[http://www.rogers.com/web/Rogers.portal?_nfpb=true&_pageLabel=contactus_page&customer_type=Residential Contact Us Mail or Fax]\". Rogers Communications. Retrieved on November 22, 2013.</ref> The company traces its origins to 1960, when [[Edward S. Rogers Jr.|Ted Rogers]] and a partner bought the [[CHFI-FM]] radio station;<ref name=History>{{cite web |url=http://your.rogers.com/aboutrogers/historyofrogers/overview.asp |title=History of Rogers |work=Rogers Communications |access-date=2012-05-31|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080202060352/http://your.rogers.com/aboutrogers/historyofrogers/overview.asp|archive-date=2008-02-02}}</ref> they then became part-owners of a group that established the [[CFTO-DT|CFTO]] television station.<ref>[https://www.broadcasting-history.ca/listing_and_histories/rogers-media Rogers Media], ''The Canadian Communications Foundation''.</ref>\n\nThe chief competitor to Rogers is [[Bell Canada]], which has a similarly extensive portfolio of radio and television media assets, as well as wireless, television distribution, and telephone services, particularly in Eastern and Central Canada. The two companies are often seen as having a [[duopoly]] on communications services in their regions, and both companies own a stake of [[Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment]]. However, Rogers also competes nationally with [[Telus]] for wireless services, and primarily indirectly with [[Shaw Communications]] for [[multichannel television in Canada|television service]].\n\n==History==\nIn 1925, [[Edward S. Rogers Sr.]] invented the world's first [[alternating current]] (AC) heater filament cathode for a [[radio tube]], which then enabled [[radio]]s to be powered by ordinary transformer-coupled household electric current.<ref name=History/> This was a breakthrough in the technology and became a key factor in popularizing radio reception. He also established the [[CFRB]] radio station in Toronto (later acquired by outside interests). In 1931, he was awarded an experimental television licence in Canada. On May 6, 1939, he was working on radar when he died suddenly due to complications of a hemorrhage, at the age of 38. He left a widow, Velma, and a five-year-old son, Edward (known as Ted). While his business interests were subsequently sold, his son later determined to carry on his father's legacy.<ref name=History/>\n\nIn 1960, [[Edward S. Rogers Jr.|Ted Rogers]] and broadcaster Joel Aldred<ref>[https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/thestar/obituary.aspx?n=joel-walkden-aldred&pid=154189621&fhid=8490 Joel Walkden Aldred]</ref> raised money to found Aldred-Rogers Broadcasting in order to purchase [[CHFI-FM|CHFI]], an FM radio station in Toronto.<ref>[http://www.broadcasting-history.ca/listing_and_histories/radio/chfi-fm CHFI-FM]</ref> Aldred-Rogers Broadcasting also became a part-owner of [[Baton Aldred Rogers Broadcasting]] (BARB), which established [[CFTO-DT|CFTO-TV]], Toronto's first private television station.<ref name=\"Nolan2001\">{{cite book|author=Michael Nolan|title=CTV, the Network that Means Business|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6c3FkFx0-uoC&pg=PA20|year=2001|publisher=University of Alberta|isbn=978-0-88864-384-1|page=20}}</ref><ref name=\"Hasselt2010\">{{cite book|author=Caroline Van Hasselt|title=High Wire Act: Ted Rogers and the Empire that Debt Built|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wt8ulI7RV9oC&pg=PT56|date=17 March 2010|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-0-470-73974-7|page=56}}</ref> In 1964, Rogers established [[CFTR (AM)|CFTR]], an AM radio station. In 1967, Rogers established Rogers Cable TV in partnership with BARB. In 1971, new [[CRTC]] regulations forced BARB to sell its 50% stake in Rogers Cable TV.\n\nIn 1979, Rogers acquired Canadian Cablesystems, and became listed on the [[Toronto Stock Exchange]] as a result. In 1980, Rogers acquired Premier Cablevision and became the largest cable company in Canada. In 1986, Rogers Cable was renamed Rogers Communications; it established operational control over [[Rogers Wireless|Cantel]], a wireless telephone company in which Rogers had a stake.\n\n===21st century===\n[[File:Rogers logo old.svg|thumb|left|200px|Rogers logo used from 2000-2015. Prior to the late 2000s, a non-flat version of the mobius strip was used.]]\nRogers Communications Inc. unveiled its new logo on January 17, 2000, marking the departure of its original logo.<ref>[http://strategyonline.ca/2000/01/17/27798-20000117/ Rogers begins corporate branding blitz] staff writer. ''Strategy''. 10 January 2000</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Rogers acquired [[Cable Atlantic]]<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/money/story/2000/09/18/rogers000918.html Rogers buys Cable Atlantic], CBC News, November 10, 2000</ref> from Newfoundland businessman [[Danny Williams (politician)|Danny Williams]].\n\nIn July 2001, Rogers Media acquired CTV Sportsnet, which was renamed as [[Sportsnet|Rogers Sportsnet]] that November. The FAN 590 sports radio station joined Rogers Media in August 2001, along with 14 Northern Ontario radio stations.<ref>[http://www.shoprogers.com/aboutrogers/historyofrogers/overview.asp?shopperID=TFGXNUHRMB1R9H338L1W1D69VBV60KW7 History of Rogers], Rogers.com</ref>\n\nIn fall 2004, several strategic transactions were executed that significantly increased Rogers exposure to the potential of the Canadian wireless market. Rogers acquired the 34% of Rogers Wireless owned by AT&T Wireless Services Inc. for $1.77 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seaboardgroup.com/main/index.php?option=content&task=view&id=56&Itemid=2|title=Rogers buys AT&T stake in cell unit|publisher=The SeaBoard Group}}</ref>\n\nOn December 2, 2008, Ted Rogers died of heart failure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20081202.wrogersobit1202/BNStory/Business/home|title=Communications giant Ted Rogers dies at 75|accessdate=5 October 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090514034015/http://business.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20081202.wrogersobit1202/BNStory/Business/home|archivedate=14 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Rogers Cable filed a complaint in an Ontario court against penalties levied under a 'Truth in Advertising' law, claiming that the amount of the penalties, and the requirements imposed by the law, were in violation of the [[Charter of Rights and Freedoms]].<ref>[https://vancouversun.com/business/Rogers+uses+charter+claim+fight+truth+advertising/6057561/story.html Rogers uses charter claim to fight truth in advertising]. ''[[The Vancouver Sun]]''. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120128230236/http://www.vancouversun.com/business/Rogers+uses+charter+claim+fight+truth+advertising/6057561/story.html |date=January 28, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe company also had to recognize the rising market trend of customers canceling or foregoing cable television service subscriptions in favour of cheaper alternate content delivery means, such as [[streaming media]] services like [[Netflix]], a demographic called \"[[cord cutters]]\" and \"[[cord nevers]].\" In response, Rogers acquired content with a speculated cost of $100 million to begin their own competing online streaming service, [[Shomi]], much like the American [[Hulu Plus]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Rogers may launch Netflix rival for $100M|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/rogers-may-launch-netflix-rival-for-100m-1.2491463|accessdate=11 January 2014|newspaper=CBC News|date=10 January 2014}}</ref> which launched November 4, 2014. Shomi subsequently shut down after only 2 years of operation, on November 30, 2016.<ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/shomi-shut-down-1.3779675|title=Web streaming service Shomi to shut down as of Nov. 30|newspaper=[[CBC News]]|date=26 September 2016|accessdate=2016-10-01}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2014, Rogers reported a 24% drop in profit compared to the previous year's second quarter.<ref name=\"Financial Post\">{{cite web|last1=Greenwood|first1=John|title=Rogers Communications Inc. profit drops 24% as revenue growth slows|url=http://business.financialpost.com/2014/07/24/rogers-communications-inc-profit-drops-24-as-revenue-growth-slows/?__lsa=cd86-34fc|website=Financial Post|accessdate=5 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Corporate governance==\nRogers Communications is traded on the [[Toronto Stock Exchange]] and on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] under ticker \"RCI\".\n\nFollowing the death of Ted Rogers in 2008, control of Rogers Communications passed to the Rogers Control Trust, a [[trust law|trust]] for which a subsidiary of [[Scotiabank]] serves as trustee. Ted's son [[Edward Rogers III]] and daughter Melinda Rogers serve, respectively, as Chair and Vice-Chair of the trust.<ref>[http://www.crtc.gc.ca/ownership/cht27.pdf CRTC ownership chart] for Rogers Communications  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070203173347/http://www.crtc.gc.ca/ownership/cht27.pdf |date=February 3, 2007 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.smartbrief.com/news/aaaa/industryPR-detail.jsp?id=98A21C69-DBFC-46D5-8E43-7F00504D54F9 Voting Control of Rogers Group of Companies to be Held in Trust for Family], Rogers Communications press release, December 22, 2008</ref>\n\n{{As of|2018|October}}, members of the [[board of directors]] of Rogers Communications are:<ref name=Directors>{{cite web|title=Rogers \u2013 Board of Directors|url=https://investors.rogers.com/corporate-governance/board-of-directors/ |accessdate=30 October 2018}}</ref> \n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n*Bonnie Brooks\n*Robert K. Burgess \n*John H. Clappison\n*Robert D\u00e9patie\n*Robert J. Gemmell\n{{col-break}}\n*Alan D. Horn \n*Philip B. Lind \n*John A. MacDonald \n*Isabelle Marcoux\n*Joe Natale \n{{col-break}}\n*David R. Peterson\n*Edward S. Rogers III\n*Loretta A. Rogers\n*Martha L. Rogers \n*Melinda M. Rogers\n{{col-end}}\n{{As of|2018|October}}, senior corporate officers of Rogers Communications are:<ref>{{cite web|title=Rogers \u2013 Senior Leadership|url=http://www.rogers.com/web/ir/overview/senior-leadership |accessdate=30 October 2018}}</ref>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n*Joe Natale \u2013 President and Chief Executive Officer\n*Jordan Banks  \u2013 President,  Media\n*Lisa Durocher \u2013 Chief Digital Officer\n*Jorge Fernandes \u2013 Chief Technology Officer\n*Phil Hartling \u2013 President, Residential\n{{col-break}}\n*Brent Johnston \u2013 President, Wireless\n*Graeme McPhail \u2013 Chief Legal and Regulatory Officer\n*Dean Prevost \u2013 President, Enterprise\n*Jim Reid \u2013 Chief Human Resources Officer\n*Tony Staffieri \u2014 Chief Financial Officer\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Assets and divisions==\n{{Main|List of assets owned by Rogers Communications}}\n[[File:RogersFirstMarkhamPlace.jpg|thumb|A Rogers store offering services from [[Rogers Wireless]], a wireless telephone subsidiary of the company]]\nAssets and divisions of Rogers Communications includes:\n{{col div}}\n*Rogers Communications Inc. \n*Rogers Cable\n*Rogers Wireless\n*Rogers Communications\n*Rogers Smart Home Monitoring\n*Rogers Media\n{{col div end}}\n===Publishing===\n{{Update|type=|date=March 2019|reason=Magazine assets sold in March 2019. As of April 2019, Rogers will no longer own these magazines}}\n[[File:Omni-City-33Dundas.jpg|thumb|[[33 Dundas Street East]] in Toronto is a complex used by [[Citytv]] and [[Omni Television|Omni]], two television networks are owned by [[Rogers Media]], a subsidiary of Rogers Communications.]]\nPrior to 2019, Rogers Publishing Limited published more than 70 consumer magazines and trade and professional publications, digital properties and directories in Canada, including ''[[Maclean's]]'', Canada's weekly newsmagazine; its French-language equivalent, ''[[L'actualit\u00e9]]''; Sportsnet Magazine''; [[Chatelaine (magazine)|Chatelaine]]''; ''[[Flare (magazine)|Flare]]''; and a variety of other magazines and their companion web sites. The publishing arm was once part of the Maclean-Hunter Publishing empire.{{citation needed|date=December 2015}} Unlike Maclean-Hunter, Rogers does not have printing facilities and has contracted out services (in 2008 contracted to Montreal-based [[TC Transcontinental]] to print magazines from their plants across Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.printcan.com/news/2012/20120904869.shtml|title=TC Transcontinental to print Rogers' magazines until 2019 - PrintCAN|website=www.printcan.com|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref>)\n\nOn June 28, 2007, Rogers offered to sell the two religious-licensed OMNI stations in Winnipeg and Vancouver as part of the Citytv deal, although the company stated that it intended to retain the multilingual-licensed OMNI stations.<ref>Robertson, Grant. [https://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20070628.wrogerz0628/BNStory/Technology/ Rogers offers to sell two stations], The Globe and Mail, June 28, 2007</ref> On July 7, Rogers also announced a takeover offer for Vancouver's multicultural station [[CHNM-TV|CHNM]]. In September 2007, Rogers has also applied to the CRTC to acquire 20 per cent of [[CablePulse 24]], a local news channel in Toronto which was previously paired with Citytv (both stations were previously owned by CHUM Limited) but was retained by CTVglobemedia in the June 8 licence approval.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2007/n2007-12.htm#18|title=ARCHIVED - Broadcasting Notice of Public Hearing CRTC 2007-12|first=Government of Canada, Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission|last=(CRTC)|date=31 August 2007|website=www.crtc.gc.ca|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref> Neither CTVglobemedia nor Rogers has, to date, announced whether this application will change future plans for the station.\n\nIn 2012, Rogers purchased [[CJNT-DT]] Montreal<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.montrealgazette.com/entertainment/television/cjnt+become+citytv+montreal+morning+show/7333836/story.html|title=CJNT may become Citytv Montreal, add morning show|last=Faguy|first=Steve|website=www.montrealgazette.com|language=en-ca|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> and on February 3, 2013, it was rebranded as City Montreal.\n\nIn March 2019, Rogers sold their magazine brands, including Maclean's, Chatelaine and HELLO! Canada, to [[St. Joseph Communications]] for an undisclosed sum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/rogers-media-magazines-1.5064054|title=Rogers Media sells Maclean's, Chatelaine and other magazines to Toronto Life publisher|last=Evans|first=Pete|date=20 March 2019|website=CBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\nIn addition to its ownership of [[Sportsnet]], acquired from [[CTV Television Network|CTV]], [[Sportsnet One]] and [[Sportsnet World]], Rogers Media operates the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] [[baseball]] team through Rogers Blue Jays Baseball Partnership and the [[Rogers Centre]] (previously known as ''SkyDome''). Through Sportsnet, Rogers Media also holds a 50% ownership in Dome Productions, a mobile production and distribution joint venture that is a leader in high-definition television production and broadcasting in Canada. Rogers also owns the naming rights to [[Rogers Arena]], home of the [[Vancouver Canucks]].,<ref>{{cite web|title=Rogers Arena: New name for home of the Vancouver Canucks|url=https://www.rogers.com/web/link/showNewsDetail?fromWhere=linkInRSSXml&rssBusiUnit=R&NewsID=1807062570|publisher=Rogers Communications|accessdate=31 October 2013}}</ref> as well as [[Rogers Place]], the home of the [[Edmonton Oilers]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Rogers Place About|url=http://www.rogersplace.com/about/|accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref>\n[[File:Rogers Centre (8028252192).jpg|thumb|The [[Rogers Centre]] is a [[multi-purpose stadium]] that is operated by the company]]\nOn August 25, 2012, Rogers Media agreed to acquire Score Media which includes [[The Score Television Network]] for $167 million, including a 10% stake of its digital business. The deal was completed on  Oct. 19, 2012.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/rogers-will-only-have-small-stake-in-score-medias-digital-growth/article4499177/ | location=Toronto | work=The Globe and Mail | title=Rogers will only have small stake in Score Media's digital growth | date=August 25, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/1056217/rogers-media-completes-acquisition-of-score-media | location = Toronto | work = newswire.ca | title = Rogers Media Completes Acquisition of Score Media | date = October 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\nCanada Inc., a joint venture between Rogers Communications and Bell Canada Owns 75% of [[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]], owns the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] of the [[National Hockey League]], [[Toronto Raptors]] of the [[National Basketball Association]], [[Toronto Argonauts]] of the [[Canadian Football League]], and [[Toronto FC]] of [[Major League Soccer]], as well as their minor league [[farm team]]s, the [[Toronto Marlies]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL), [[Raptors 905]] of the [[NBA G League]] and [[Toronto FC II]] of the [[USL League One]], respectively.\n\n====National Hockey League====\n{{main|NHL on Sportsnet}}\nOn November 26, 2013, Rogers Communications Inc, unveiled the details of a 12-year, [[Canadian dollar|C]]$5.2 billion partnership with the [[National Hockey League]] which began in the [[2014\u201315 NHL season|2014\u201315 season]]. This will give Rogers the controlling stake for national broadcast and digital rights of the NHL and will ultimately give them the ability to stream all NHL feeds on all of their current platforms replacing both [[TSN Hockey|Bell Media]] and [[Hockey Night in Canada|CBC Sports]] as the national broadcast and cable television rightsholders respectively. The effects of this deal will shift the balance of power in the country's broadcast industry as it will drive demand for Rogers Cable TV subscriptions. This transaction marks the first time a first-class North American-wide sports league has allowed all its national right to one company on a long-term basis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/2013/11/26/rogers-to-pay-nhl-5-2b-over-12-years-for-national-hockey-rights/|title=NHL, Rogers Communications Inc reach 12-year broadcast deal worth $5.2-billion|author=Christine Dobby|date=26 November 2013|work=Financial Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=693152|title=NHL, Rogers Communications announce 12-year, $5.2 billion TV, multimedia deal|work=NHL.com}}</ref> As part of the deal, Rogers also took over Canadian distribution of the [[NHL Centre Ice]] and GameCentre Live services. National [[NHL on Sportsnet|English-language coverage]] of the NHL is carried primarily by Rogers' [[Sportsnet]] group of specialty channels; Sportsnet holds an exclusive window for games played on Wednesday nights. ''[[Hockey Night in Canada]]'' was maintained and expanded under the deal, airing up to seven games nationally on Saturday nights throughout the regular season across [[CBC Television]], the Sportsnet networks, Rogers-owned television network [[Citytv]], and [[FX Canada]]. While CBC maintains Rogers-produced NHL coverage during the regular season and playoffs through a [[Brokered programming|time-brokerage]] agreement with the company, Rogers assumes editorial control and the ownership of any advertising revenue from the telecasts.<ref name=gandm-howcbclost>{{cite news|last1=Shoalts|first1=David|title=Hockey Night in Canada: How CBC lost it all|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/hockey/hockey-night-in-canada-how-cbc-lost-it-all/article21072643/|website=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=October 11, 2014}}</ref> Citytv (and later Sportsnet) also airs a Sunday night game of the week, ''Rogers Hometown Hockey'', which features a pre-game show originating from various Canadian communities. Sportsnet's networks also air occasional games involving all-U.S. matchups.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/nearly-500-nhl-games-to-air-under-rogers-deal/ |title=500-plus NHL games to air under Rogers deal | work=Sportsnet | date=February 4, 2014 | accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref><ref name=gandm-rogersnhl14>{{cite news|title=Rogers reaches 12-year broadcast deal with NHL worth $5.2-billion|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/rogers-reaches-12-year-broadcast-deal-with-nhl-worth-52-billion/article15600412/|work=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=November 26, 2013|location=Toronto|date=November 27, 2013}}</ref><ref name=cbcnews-rogersnhl>{{cite news|title=Rogers scores national NHL TV rights for $5.2B|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/rogers-scores-national-nhl-tv-rights-for-5-2b-1.2440645|work=CBC News|accessdate=November 26, 2013}}</ref><ref name=torstar-hugeblow>{{cite news|title=NHL deal with Rogers a huge blow to TSN and CBC: Mudhar|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/hockey/2013/11/26/nhl_deal_with_rogers_a_huge_blow_to_tsn_and_cbc_mudhar.html|work=Toronto Star|accessdate=November 26, 2013|date=November 26, 2013}}</ref><ref name=cbcsports-rogers14>{{cite news|title=CBC partners with Rogers in landmark NHL rights deal|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/nhl/cbc-partners-with-rogers-in-landmark-nhl-rights-deal-1.2440326|work=CBC Sports|accessdate=November 26, 2013}}</ref><ref name=gandm-hnicnewgame>{{cite news|last1=Bradshaw|first1=James|title=Rogers' Hockey Night in Canada will be a whole new game for viewers|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/hockey/canadians-prepare-for-more-game-coverage-storytelling-with-new-nhl-season/article20930976/?page=all|accessdate=October 12, 2014|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>\n[[File:Sportsnet Mobile Studio in Regina.jpg|thumb|A [[Sportsnet]] mobile studio in [[Regina, Saskatchewan|Regina]] during [[Sportsnet]]'s ''Rogers Hometown Hockey'' tour]]\nUnder a sub-licensing agreement with Rogers, [[Quebecor Media]] holds national [[French language|French-language]] rights to the NHL, with all coverage airing on its specialty channel [[TVA Sports]]. TVA Sports' flagship broadcasts on Saturday nights focus primarily on the [[Montreal Canadiens]].<ref name=nhl-tvasports>{{cite web|title=NHL, TVA Sports launch French-language agreement|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=729553|website=NHL.com|accessdate=21 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=torstar-rogersnhl14>{{cite news|title=NHL signs 12-year TV, Internet deal with Rogers; CBC keeps \u2018Hockey Night in Canada\u2019|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/hockey/2013/11/26/nhl_signs_12year_broadcast_deal_with_rogers_cbc_keeps_hockey_night_in_canada.html|work=Toronto Star|accessdate=November 26, 2013|date=November 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nRogers sought to increase the prominence of NHL content on digital platforms by re-launching the NHL's digital [[out-of-market sports package]] GameCentre Live as Rogers NHL GameCentre Live, adding the ability to stream all of Rogers' national NHL telecasts, along with in-market streaming of regional games for teams whose regional rights are held by Sportsnet.<ref name=np-everygame>{{cite news|title=Rogers will allow you to watch even more NHL games online this season \u2026 just not all of them|url=http://sports.nationalpost.com/2014/09/03/how-rogers-will-allow-you-to-watch-even-more-nhl-games-online-this-season-just-not-all-of-them/|accessdate=September 18, 2014|work=National Post|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140918202857/http://sports.nationalpost.com/2014/09/03/how-rogers-will-allow-you-to-watch-even-more-nhl-games-online-this-season-just-not-all-of-them/|archivedate=September 18, 2014}}</ref> ''GamePlus''\u2014an additional mode featuring alternate camera angles intended for a [[second screen]] experience, such as angles focusing on certain players, net and referee cameras, and a Skycam in selected venues, was also added exclusively for GameCentre Live subscribers who are subscribed to Rogers' cable, internet, or wireless services.<ref name=globeandmail-advisor>{{cite news|title=How do you like your hockey? Rogers, NHL want to find out|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/industry-news/marketing/how-do-you-watch-hockey-rogers-nhl-launch-listening-tour-to-find-out/article16695957/|accessdate=July 15, 2014|work=The Globe & Mail|date=February 4, 2014}}</ref><ref name=gandm-gameplus>{{cite web|title=Rogers GamePlus has NHL angles covered, but app will come at a price|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/hockey/rogers-gameplus-has-nhl-angles-covered-but-app-will-come-at-a-price/article20958049/|website=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=October 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the lead-up to the 2014-15 season, Rogers began to promote its networks as the new home of the NHL through a multi-platform advertising campaign; the campaign featured advertising and cross-promotions across Rogers' properties, such as [[The Shopping Channel]], which began to feature presentations of NHL merchandise, and its parenting magazine ''[[Today's Parent]]'', which began to feature hockey-themed stories in its issues.<ref name=globeandmail-adbuys>{{cite news|title=Rogers ramps up NHL ad buys|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/industry-news/marketing/rogers-ramps-up-nhl-ad-buys/article19479990/|accessdate=July 15, 2014|work=The Globe & Mail|date=July 6, 2014}}</ref> On May 28, 2014, Rogers announced a six-year sponsorship deal with [[Scotiabank]], which saw the bank become the title sponsor for ''Wednesday Night Hockey'' and ''[[Hockey Day in Canada]]'', and become a sponsor for other segments and initiatives throughout Rogers' NHL coverage.<ref name=torstar-scotiabank>{{cite web|title=Rogers and Scotiabank reach NHL sponsorship deal|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2014/05/28/rogers_and_scotiabank_reach_nhl_sponsorship_deal.html|work=Toronto Star|accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn October 6, 2014, Rogers and NHL began their media sales venture in which Rogers will lead all Canadian national NHL media sales across its owned and operated broadcast and digital platforms as well as ad sales for League-owned digital assets in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=733209|title=NHL and Rogers announce media sales partnership|work=NHL.com}}</ref>\n\n==Digital products and services==\n===OutRank by Rogers===\n<!-- The page [[OutRank by Rogers]] redirects here. -->\n\nIn 2011, a partnership was formed between Rogers Communications and [[Yodle, Inc]] to provide a suite of digital marketing services to Canadian small, medium, and enterprise size business.<ref>{{cite web|title=Multi-Location: ONE Solution|url=http://www.rogersoutrank.com/national-brands|publisher=Outrank by Rogers|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Thomas|first1=Ryan|title=Why Most Renovations Start In The Kitchen And What Homeowners Might Be Missing|url=https://online.wsj.com/article/PR-CO-20130507-912991.html|publisher=[[Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=30 September 2014|quote=OutRank by Rogers helps small businesses connect with potential customers.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Yodle Shows Strong Momentum in a Record-Breaking 2012|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/press-release/20130211/yodle-shows-strong-momentum-record-breaking-2012-1075556|accessdate=17 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Getting customers, a keyword at a time|url=http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=391edc09-d5a2-478a-9b4e-7f76a5771101|publisher=[[Vancouver Sun]]|accessdate=17 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Why Most Renovations Start In The Kitchen And What Homeowners Might Be Missing|url=https://online.wsj.com/article/PR-CO-20130507-912991.html|publisher=[[Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=17 October 2014}}</ref> These solutions have been deployed under the name OutRank by Rogers and operate as a business unit within the company. Services include [[search engine optimization]], [[mobile marketing]], [[social media marketing]], [[pay per click]], and [[analytics]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Arellano|first1=Nestor|title=Rogers targets small biz with new online marketing suite|url=http://www.itbusiness.ca/news/rogers-targets-small-biz-with-new-online-marketing-suite/16907|quote=Called Outrank, the service promises to help companies generate more inbound phone calls and emails by offering a suite of products that include Web site design, search engine optimization (SEO) services, campaign tracking and paid search marketing.|publisher=[[ITBusiness]]|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Roseman|first1=Ellen|title=Refunds can be elusive without media help: Roseman|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/personal_finance/2013/12/06/refunds_can_be_elusive_without_media_help_roseman.html|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=mobile1>{{cite web|last1=Atchison|first1=Chris|title=Creating a Mobile Website|url=http://www.connectedforbusiness.ca/business/creating-a-mobile-website/|publisher=Connected for Business|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Condron|first1=Frank|title=Don\u2019t Ignore Online Customers|url=http://www.profitguide.com/news/don%E2%80%99t-let-your-online-presence-miss-out-48473|publisher=[[Profit (magazine)|Profit]]|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref> The opening was announced in January 2012 with the launch of their first client, Ontario-based CLS Roofing.<ref>{{cite web|last=Laermer|first=Emily|title=Online marketer Yodle expanding into Canada|url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20120119/SMALLBIZ/120119863|work=Crain's New York Business|publisher=Crain Communications Inc.}}</ref> OutRank by Rogers is a Google Premier SMB Partner and promotes [[Responsive web design|responsive]] web design.<ref>{{cite web|title=Find a Premier SMB Partner to help grow your business|url=https://www.google.ca/intl/en/ads/premiersmbpartner/advertisers-findpartner.html|publisher=[[Google]]|accessdate=17 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=OutRank by Rogers' Small Business Customers See 60% Rise in Web Traffic From Mobile Devices|url=http://www.advfn.com/news_OutRank-by-Rogers-Small-Business-Customers-See-60_56169361.html|accessdate=17 October 2014}}</ref> The company is a donor to the [[Ronald McDonald House Charities Canada#Toronto|Ronald Mcdonald House of Toronto]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Home for Dinner Photos - Outrank by Rogers|url=http://rmhtoronto.org/Home-for-Dinner-Photos-Outrank-by-Rogers|publisher=[[Ronald McDonald House Charities]]|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Zoocasa===\nIn 2008, Rogers Communications launched '''Zoocasa''', an online real estate listing service. The company later became a licensed real estate brokerage and in May 2013, the website relaunched to allow homebuyers to find properties and agents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/real_estate/2015/06/09/rogers-shuts-down-discount-brokerage-zoocasa.html|title=Rogers shuts down discount brokerage Zoocasa {{!}} Toronto Star|website=thestar.com|access-date=2016-10-16}}</ref> The service also provided rebates on real estate commissions to buyers and sellers. Zoocasa was shut down on June 22, 2015. The website's domain and technology were purchased for $350,000 and the website relaunched on July 2, 2015 under new ownership.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/real_estate/2015/07/02/rogers-communications-sells-zoocasa-real-estate-site.html|title=Rogers Communications sells Zoocasa real estate site {{!}} Toronto Star|website=thestar.com|accessdate=2016-10-16}}</ref>\n\n=== Texture ===\n[[Texture (app)|Texture]] (previously known as Next Issue) was a digital magazine app introduced to the Canadian market by Rogers in 2013.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/rogers-new-magazine-app-caters-to-digital-reading-habits/article26599368/|title=Rogers revamps Next Issue app to cater to digital reading habits|last=Bradshaw|first=James|date=30 September 2015|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|access-date=24 December 2017}}</ref> The service had a monthly subscription fee that gave readers access to over 200 magazines in English and French.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.texture.ca/en/newsstand/|title=Texture Canada Catalog|access-date=24 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nTexture was purchased by Apple in 2018 and the service discontinued in 2019 in favor of [[Apple News+]].\n\n=== Rogers Bank ===\n'''Rogers Bank''' ({{lang-fr|Banque Rogers}}) is a Canadian [[financial services]] company wholly owned by Rogers Communications. Rogers applied to the [[Minister of Finance (Canada)|Minister of Finance]] under the ''[[Bank Act (Canada)|Bank Act]]'' for permission to establish a Schedule I bank (a domestic bank that may accept deposits) in summer 2011.<ref>{{cite news| title=Broadcaster, Internet Provider, Wireless Carrier .. Bank?| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2013/09/07/rogers-credit-card_n_3882710.html| accessdate=2 April 2017|work=[[The Huffington Post]]}}</ref> At launch, Rogers Bank offered a Rogers-branded [[credit card]] targeted at existing customers.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://business.financialpost.com/2013/05/03/rogers-gets-closer-to-starting-banking-business/| title=Rogers gets closer to starting banking business| newspaper=[[Financial Post]]| last=Dobby| first=Christine| date=2013-05-03| accessdate=2013-09-23}}</ref> A companion card branded for Rogers subsidiary [[Fido Solutions|Fido]] was introduced in 2016.<ref>{{cite news| last1=Behar| first1=Rose| title=Fido launches travel-friendly cash back MasterCard through Rogers Bank| url=https://mobilesyrup.com/2016/07/28/fido-launches-travel-friendly-cash-back-mastercard-through-rogers-bank/| accessdate=November 13, 2017| work=MobileSyrup| date=July 28, 2016}}</ref> The bank offers three categories of credit card to Canadians: Fido [[Mastercard]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://financefeat.com/rogers-mastercard/|title=Review: Rogers MasterCard Credit Cards|date=2019-03-13|website=Financefeat|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref> Rogers Platinum Mastercard,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://financefeat.com/rogers-platinum-mastercard/|title=Review: Rogers Platinum MasterCard Credit Card|date=2019-03-15|website=Financefeat|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref> and Rogers World Elite Mastercard.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://financefeat.com/rogers-world-elite-mastercard/|title=Review: Rogers World Elite Mastercard Credit Card|date=2019-03-18|website=Financefeat|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Canada|Companies}}\n*[[Media ownership in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Rogers Communications}}\n* {{official website|https://www.rogers.com/}}\n\n{{Rogers Communications}}\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Telecommunications}}\n{{Internet service providers of Canada}}\n{{S&P/TSX 60}}\n{{Major telecommunications companies}}\n{{Canadian banks}}\n{{NHL}}\n{{Toronto Blue Jays owners}}\n{{MLBOwners}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:1960 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies established in 1960]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Toronto Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Rogers Communications| ]]\n[[Category:Toronto Blue Jays owners]]\n[[Category:Canadian brands]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies established in 1960]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1960]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian telecommunications company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name          = Rogers Communications Inc.\n| logo          = Rogers logo.svg\n| logo_caption  = Rogers logo, used since 2015\n| image         = Rogers AT&T Centre.JPG\n| image_size    = 220px\n| image_caption = The [[Rogers Building (Toronto)|Rogers Building]] in Toronto, Ontario\n| type          = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as     = {{TSX|RCI.A|RCI.B}}<br />[[S&P/TSX 60|S&P/TSX 60 component]]\n| founder       = [[Edward S. Rogers Jr.|Ted Rogers]]\n| key_people    = [[Edward S. Rogers III]] {{small|(Chairman)}}<ref name=Directors/><br />Joe Natale {{small|(President & CEO)}}\n| industry      = [[Telecommunications]]<br/>[[Mass media]]\n| products      = [[Landline]] and [[mobile phone|mobile]] telephony, [[Internet]] services, [[digital television]], [[broadcasting]], [[cable TV]], [[publishing]]\n| revenue       = [[Canadian dollar|C$]]14.143 billion (2017)<ref name=\"rogers.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rogers.com/web/ir/financial-reporting/financial-historyf|title=Rogers Investor Relations|website=Rogers Investor Relations|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref>\n| net_income    = C$1.821 billion (2017)<ref name=\"rogers.com\"/>\n| assets        = C$29.175 billion (2015)<ref name=\"rogers.com\"/>\n| equity        = C$5.745 billion (2015)\n| num_employees = 26,000 (2013)<ref name=\"rogers.com\"/>\n| subsid        = {{ubl|[[Fido Solutions]]|[[Chatr]]|[[Rogers Communications#Rogers Bank|Rogers Bank]]|[[Rogers Cable]]|[[Rogers Media]]|[[Rogers Telecom]]|[[Rogers Wireless]]}}\n| homepage      = {{URL|rogers.com}}\n| foundation    = 1960<ref>[http://about.rogers.com/About/Our_History.aspx About Rogers: Our History] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004095504/http://about.rogers.com/About/Our_History.aspx |date=2013-10-04 }}, rogers.com.</ref>\n| location      = 333 [[Bloor Street]] East<br />[[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]<br />M4W 1G9\n}}\n\n'''Rogers Communications Inc.''' is a Canadian communications and media company. It operates primarily in the fields of [[mobile phone operator|wireless communications]], [[cable television]], [[telephony]] and [[Internet access|Internet connectivity]], with significant additional [[telecommunications]] and [[mass media]] assets. Rogers has its headquarters in [[Toronto]], Ontario.<ref>\"[http://www.rogers.com/web/Rogers.portal?_nfpb=true&_pageLabel=contactus_page&customer_type=Residential Contact Us Mail or Fax]\". Rogers Communications. Retrieved on November 22, 2013.</ref> The company traces its origins to 1960, when [[Edward S. Rogers Jr.|Ted Rogers]] and a partner bought the [[CHFI-FM]] radio station;<ref name=History>{{cite web |url=http://your.rogers.com/aboutrogers/historyofrogers/overview.asp |title=History of Rogers |work=Rogers Communications |access-date=2012-05-31|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080202060352/http://your.rogers.com/aboutrogers/historyofrogers/overview.asp|archive-date=2008-02-02}}</ref> they then became part-owners of a group that established the [[CFTO-DT|CFTO]] television station.<ref>[https://www.broadcasting-history.ca/listing_and_histories/rogers-media Rogers Media], ''The Canadian Communications Foundation''.</ref>\n\nThe chief competitor to Rogers is [[Bell Canada]], which has a similarly extensive portfolio of radio and television media assets, as well as wireless, television distribution, and telephone services, particularly in Eastern and Central Canada. The two companies are often seen as having a [[duopoly]] on communications services in their regions, and both companies own a stake of [[Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment]]. However, Rogers also competes nationally with [[Telus]] for wireless services, and primarily indirectly with [[Shaw Communications]] for [[multichannel television in Canada|television service]].\n\n==History==\nIn 1925, [[Edward S. Rogers Sr.]] invented the world's first [[alternating current]] (AC) heater filament cathode for a [[radio tube]], which then enabled [[radio]]s to be powered by ordinary transformer-coupled household electric current.<ref name=History/> This was a breakthrough in the technology and became a key factor in popularizing radio reception. He also established the [[CFRB]] radio station in Toronto (later acquired by outside interests). In 1931, he was awarded an experimental television licence in Canada. On May 6, 1939, he was working on radar when he died suddenly due to complications of a hemorrhage, at the age of 38. He left a widow, Velma, and a five-year-old son, Edward (known as Ted). While his business interests were subsequently sold, his son later determined to carry on his father's legacy.<ref name=History/>\n\nIn 1960, [[Edward S. Rogers Jr.|Ted Rogers]] and broadcaster Joel Aldred<ref>[https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/thestar/obituary.aspx?n=joel-walkden-aldred&pid=154189621&fhid=8490 Joel Walkden Aldred]</ref> raised money to found Aldred-Rogers Broadcasting in order to purchase [[CHFI-FM|CHFI]], an FM radio station in Toronto.<ref>[http://www.broadcasting-history.ca/listing_and_histories/radio/chfi-fm CHFI-FM]</ref> Aldred-Rogers Broadcasting also became a part-owner of [[Baton Aldred Rogers Broadcasting]] (BARB), which established [[CFTO-DT|CFTO-TV]], Toronto's first private television station.<ref name=\"Nolan2001\">{{cite book|author=Michael Nolan|title=CTV, the Network that Means Business|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6c3FkFx0-uoC&pg=PA20|year=2001|publisher=University of Alberta|isbn=978-0-88864-384-1|page=20}}</ref><ref name=\"Hasselt2010\">{{cite book|author=Caroline Van Hasselt|title=High Wire Act: Ted Rogers and the Empire that Debt Built|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wt8ulI7RV9oC&pg=PT56|date=17 March 2010|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-0-470-73974-7|page=56}}</ref> In 1964, Rogers established [[CFTR (AM)|CFTR]], an AM radio station. In 1967, Rogers established Rogers Cable TV in partnership with BARB. In 1971, new [[CRTC]] regulations forced BARB to sell its 50% stake in Rogers Cable TV.\n\nIn 1979, Rogers acquired Canadian Cablesystems, and became listed on the [[Toronto Stock Exchange]] as a result. In 1980, Rogers acquired Premier Cablevision and became the largest cable company in Canada. In 1986, Rogers Cable was renamed Rogers Communications; it established operational control over [[Rogers Wireless|Cantel]], a wireless telephone company in which Rogers had a stake.\n\n===21st century===\n[[File:Rogers logo old.svg|thumb|left|200px|Rogers logo used from 2000-2015. Prior to the late 2000s, a non-flat version of the mobius strip was used.]]\nRogers Communications Inc. unveiled its new logo on January 17, 2000, marking the departure of its original logo.<ref>[http://strategyonline.ca/2000/01/17/27798-20000117/ Rogers begins corporate branding blitz] staff writer. ''Strategy''. 10 January 2000</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Rogers acquired [[Cable Atlantic]]<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/money/story/2000/09/18/rogers000918.html Rogers buys Cable Atlantic], CBC News, November 10, 2000</ref> from Newfoundland businessman [[Danny Williams (politician)|Danny Williams]].\n\nIn July 2001, Rogers Media acquired CTV Sportsnet, which was renamed as [[Sportsnet|Rogers Sportsnet]] that November. The FAN 590 sports radio station joined Rogers Media in August 2001, along with 14 Northern Ontario radio stations.<ref>[http://www.shoprogers.com/aboutrogers/historyofrogers/overview.asp?shopperID=TFGXNUHRMB1R9H338L1W1D69VBV60KW7 History of Rogers], Rogers.com</ref>\n\nIn fall 2004, several strategic transactions were executed that significantly increased Rogers exposure to the potential of the Canadian wireless market. Rogers acquired the 34% of Rogers Wireless owned by AT&T Wireless Services Inc. for $1.77 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seaboardgroup.com/main/index.php?option=content&task=view&id=56&Itemid=2|title=Rogers buys AT&T stake in cell unit|publisher=The SeaBoard Group}}</ref>\n\nOn December 2, 2008, Ted Rogers died of heart failure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20081202.wrogersobit1202/BNStory/Business/home|title=Communications giant Ted Rogers dies at 75|accessdate=5 October 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090514034015/http://business.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20081202.wrogersobit1202/BNStory/Business/home|archivedate=14 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Rogers Cable filed a complaint in an Ontario court against penalties levied under a 'Truth in Advertising' law, claiming that the amount of the penalties, and the requirements imposed by the law, were in violation of the [[Charter of Rights and Freedoms]].<ref>[https://vancouversun.com/business/Rogers+uses+charter+claim+fight+truth+advertising/6057561/story.html Rogers uses charter claim to fight truth in advertising]. ''[[The Vancouver Sun]]''. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120128230236/http://www.vancouversun.com/business/Rogers+uses+charter+claim+fight+truth+advertising/6057561/story.html |date=January 28, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe company also had to recognize the rising market trend of customers canceling or foregoing cable television service subscriptions in favour of cheaper alternate content delivery means, such as [[streaming media]] services like [[Netflix]], a demographic called \"[[cord cutters]]\" and \"[[cord nevers]].\" In response, Rogers acquired content with a speculated cost of $100 million to begin their own competing online streaming service, [[Shomi]], much like the American [[Hulu Plus]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Rogers may launch Netflix rival for $100M|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/rogers-may-launch-netflix-rival-for-100m-1.2491463|accessdate=11 January 2014|newspaper=CBC News|date=10 January 2014}}</ref> which launched November 4, 2014. Shomi subsequently shut down after only 2 years of operation, on November 30, 2016.<ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/shomi-shut-down-1.3779675|title=Web streaming service Shomi to shut down as of Nov. 30|newspaper=[[CBC News]]|date=26 September 2016|accessdate=2016-10-01}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2014, Rogers reported a 24% drop in profit compared to the previous year's second quarter.<ref name=\"Financial Post\">{{cite web|last1=Greenwood|first1=John|title=Rogers Communications Inc. profit drops 24% as revenue growth slows|url=http://business.financialpost.com/2014/07/24/rogers-communications-inc-profit-drops-24-as-revenue-growth-slows/?__lsa=cd86-34fc|website=Financial Post|accessdate=5 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Corporate governance==\nRogers Communications is traded on the [[Toronto Stock Exchange]] and on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] under ticker \"RCI\".\n\nFollowing the death of Ted Rogers in 2008, control of Rogers Communications passed to the Rogers Control Trust, a [[trust law|trust]] for which a subsidiary of [[Scotiabank]] serves as trustee. Ted's son [[Edward Rogers III]] and daughter Melinda Rogers serve, respectively, as Chair and Vice-Chair of the trust.<ref>[http://www.crtc.gc.ca/ownership/cht27.pdf CRTC ownership chart] for Rogers Communications  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070203173347/http://www.crtc.gc.ca/ownership/cht27.pdf |date=February 3, 2007 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.smartbrief.com/news/aaaa/industryPR-detail.jsp?id=98A21C69-DBFC-46D5-8E43-7F00504D54F9 Voting Control of Rogers Group of Companies to be Held in Trust for Family], Rogers Communications press release, December 22, 2008</ref>\n\n{{As of|2018|October}}, members of the [[board of directors]] of Rogers Communications are:<ref name=Directors>{{cite web|title=Rogers \u2013 Board of Directors|url=https://investors.rogers.com/corporate-governance/board-of-directors/ |accessdate=30 October 2018}}</ref> \n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n*Bonnie Brooks\n*Robert K. Burgess \n*John H. Clappison\n*Robert D\u00e9patie\n*Robert J. Gemmell\n{{col-break}}\n*Alan D. Horn \n*Philip B. Lind \n*John A. MacDonald \n*Isabelle Marcoux\n*Joe Natale \n{{col-break}}\n*David R. Peterson\n*Edward S. Rogers III\n*Loretta A. Rogers\n*Martha L. Rogers \n*Melinda M. Rogers\n{{col-end}}\n{{As of|2018|October}}, senior corporate officers of Rogers Communications are:<ref>{{cite web|title=Rogers \u2013 Senior Leadership|url=http://www.rogers.com/web/ir/overview/senior-leadership |accessdate=30 October 2018}}</ref>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n*Joe Natale \u2013 President and Chief Executive Officer\n*Jordan Banks  \u2013 President,  Media\n*Lisa Durocher \u2013 Chief Digital Officer\n*Jorge Fernandes \u2013 Chief Technology Officer\n*Phil Hartling \u2013 President, Residential\n{{col-break}}\n*Brent Johnston \u2013 President, Wireless\n*Graeme McPhail \u2013 Chief Legal and Regulatory Officer\n*Dean Prevost \u2013 President, Enterprise\n*Jim Reid \u2013 Chief Human Resources Officer\n*Tony Staffieri \u2014 Chief Financial Officer\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Assets and divisions==\n{{Main|List of assets owned by Rogers Communications}}\n[[File:RogersFirstMarkhamPlace.jpg|thumb|A Rogers store offering services from [[Rogers Wireless]], a wireless telephone subsidiary of the company]]\nAssets and divisions of Rogers Communications includes:\n{{col div}}\n*Rogers Communications Inc. \n*Rogers Cable\n*Rogers Wireless\n*Rogers Communications\n*Rogers Smart Home Monitoring\n*Rogers Media\n{{col div end}}\n===Publishing===\n{{Update|type=|date=March 2019|reason=Magazine assets sold in March 2019. As of April 2019, Rogers will no longer own these magazines}}\n[[File:Omni-City-33Dundas.jpg|thumb|[[33 Dundas Street East]] in Toronto is a complex used by [[Citytv]] and [[Omni Television|Omni]], two television networks are owned by [[Rogers Media]], a subsidiary of Rogers Communications.]]\nPrior to 2019, Rogers Publishing Limited published more than 70 consumer magazines and trade and professional publications, digital properties and directories in Canada, including ''[[Maclean's]]'', Canada's weekly newsmagazine; its French-language equivalent, ''[[L'actualit\u00e9]]''; Sportsnet Magazine''; [[Chatelaine (magazine)|Chatelaine]]''; ''[[Flare (magazine)|Flare]]''; and a variety of other magazines and their companion web sites. The publishing arm was once part of the Maclean-Hunter Publishing empire.{{citation needed|date=December 2015}} Unlike Maclean-Hunter, Rogers does not have printing facilities and has contracted out services (in 2008 contracted to Montreal-based [[TC Transcontinental]] to print magazines from their plants across Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.printcan.com/news/2012/20120904869.shtml|title=TC Transcontinental to print Rogers' magazines until 2019 - PrintCAN|website=www.printcan.com|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref>)\n\nOn June 28, 2007, Rogers offered to sell the two religious-licensed OMNI stations in Winnipeg and Vancouver as part of the Citytv deal, although the company stated that it intended to retain the multilingual-licensed OMNI stations.<ref>Robertson, Grant. [https://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20070628.wrogerz0628/BNStory/Technology/ Rogers offers to sell two stations], The Globe and Mail, June 28, 2007</ref> On July 7, Rogers also announced a takeover offer for Vancouver's multicultural station [[CHNM-TV|CHNM]]. In September 2007, Rogers has also applied to the CRTC to acquire 20 per cent of [[CablePulse 24]], a local news channel in Toronto which was previously paired with Citytv (both stations were previously owned by CHUM Limited) but was retained by CTVglobemedia in the June 8 licence approval.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2007/n2007-12.htm#18|title=ARCHIVED - Broadcasting Notice of Public Hearing CRTC 2007-12|first=Government of Canada, Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission|last=(CRTC)|date=31 August 2007|website=www.crtc.gc.ca|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref> Neither CTVglobemedia nor Rogers has, to date, announced whether this application will change future plans for the station.\n\nIn 2012, Rogers purchased [[CJNT-DT]] Montreal<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.montrealgazette.com/entertainment/television/cjnt+become+citytv+montreal+morning+show/7333836/story.html|title=CJNT may become Citytv Montreal, add morning show|last=Faguy|first=Steve|website=www.montrealgazette.com|language=en-ca|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> and on February 3, 2013, it was rebranded as City Montreal.\n\nIn March 2019, Rogers sold their magazine brands, including Maclean's, Chatelaine and HELLO! Canada, to [[St. Joseph Communications]] for an undisclosed sum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/rogers-media-magazines-1.5064054|title=Rogers Media sells Maclean's, Chatelaine and other magazines to Toronto Life publisher|last=Evans|first=Pete|date=20 March 2019|website=CBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\nIn addition to its ownership of [[Sportsnet]], acquired from [[CTV Television Network|CTV]], [[Sportsnet One]] and [[Sportsnet World]], Rogers Media operates the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] [[baseball]] team through Rogers Blue Jays Baseball Partnership and the [[Rogers Centre]] (previously known as ''SkyDome''). Through Sportsnet, Rogers Media also holds a 50% ownership in Dome Productions, a mobile production and distribution joint venture that is a leader in high-definition television production and broadcasting in Canada. Rogers also owns the naming rights to [[Rogers Arena]], home of the [[Vancouver Canucks]].,<ref>{{cite web|title=Rogers Arena: New name for home of the Vancouver Canucks|url=https://www.rogers.com/web/link/showNewsDetail?fromWhere=linkInRSSXml&rssBusiUnit=R&NewsID=1807062570|publisher=Rogers Communications|accessdate=31 October 2013}}</ref> as well as [[Rogers Place]], the home of the [[Edmonton Oilers]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Rogers Place About|url=http://www.rogersplace.com/about/|accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref>\n[[File:Rogers Centre (8028252192).jpg|thumb|The [[Rogers Centre]] is a [[multi-purpose stadium]] that is operated by the company]]\nOn August 25, 2012, Rogers Media agreed to acquire Score Media which includes [[The Score Television Network]] for $167 million, including a 10% stake of its digital business. The deal was completed on  Oct. 19, 2012.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/rogers-will-only-have-small-stake-in-score-medias-digital-growth/article4499177/ | location=Toronto | work=The Globe and Mail | title=Rogers will only have small stake in Score Media's digital growth | date=August 25, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/1056217/rogers-media-completes-acquisition-of-score-media | location = Toronto | work = newswire.ca | title = Rogers Media Completes Acquisition of Score Media | date = October 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\nCanada Inc., a joint venture between Rogers Communications and Bell Canada Owns 75% of [[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]], owns the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] of the [[National Hockey League]], [[Toronto Raptors]] of the [[National Basketball Association]], [[Toronto Argonauts]] of the [[Canadian Football League]], and [[Toronto FC]] of [[Major League Soccer]], as well as their minor league [[farm team]]s, the [[Toronto Marlies]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL), [[Raptors 905]] of the [[NBA G League]] and [[Toronto FC II]] of the [[USL League One]], respectively.\n\n====National Hockey League====\n{{main|NHL on Sportsnet}}\nOn November 26, 2013, Rogers Communications Inc, unveiled the details of a 12-year, [[Canadian dollar|C]]$5.2 billion partnership with the [[National Hockey League]] which began in the [[2014\u201315 NHL season|2014\u201315 season]]. This will give Rogers the controlling stake for national broadcast and digital rights of the NHL and will ultimately give them the ability to stream all NHL feeds on all of their current platforms replacing both [[TSN Hockey|Bell Media]] and [[Hockey Night in Canada|CBC Sports]] as the national broadcast and cable television rightsholders respectively. The effects of this deal will shift the balance of power in the country's broadcast industry as it will drive demand for Rogers Cable TV subscriptions. This transaction marks the first time a first-class North American-wide sports league has allowed all its national right to one company on a long-term basis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/2013/11/26/rogers-to-pay-nhl-5-2b-over-12-years-for-national-hockey-rights/|title=NHL, Rogers Communications Inc reach 12-year broadcast deal worth $5.2-billion|author=Christine Dobby|date=26 November 2013|work=Financial Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=693152|title=NHL, Rogers Communications announce 12-year, $5.2 billion TV, multimedia deal|work=NHL.com}}</ref> As part of the deal, Rogers also took over Canadian distribution of the [[NHL Centre Ice]] and GameCentre Live services. National [[NHL on Sportsnet|English-language coverage]] of the NHL is carried primarily by Rogers' [[Sportsnet]] group of specialty channels; Sportsnet holds an exclusive window for games played on Wednesday nights. ''[[Hockey Night in Canada]]'' was maintained and expanded under the deal, airing up to seven games nationally on Saturday nights throughout the regular season across [[CBC Television]], the Sportsnet networks, Rogers-owned television network [[Citytv]], and [[FX Canada]]. While CBC maintains Rogers-produced NHL coverage during the regular season and playoffs through a [[Brokered programming|time-brokerage]] agreement with the company, Rogers assumes editorial control and the ownership of any advertising revenue from the telecasts.<ref name=gandm-howcbclost>{{cite news|last1=Shoalts|first1=David|title=Hockey Night in Canada: How CBC lost it all|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/hockey/hockey-night-in-canada-how-cbc-lost-it-all/article21072643/|website=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=October 11, 2014}}</ref> Citytv (and later Sportsnet) also airs a Sunday night game of the week, ''Rogers Hometown Hockey'', which features a pre-game show originating from various Canadian communities. Sportsnet's networks also air occasional games involving all-U.S. matchups.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/nearly-500-nhl-games-to-air-under-rogers-deal/ |title=500-plus NHL games to air under Rogers deal | work=Sportsnet | date=February 4, 2014 | accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref><ref name=gandm-rogersnhl14>{{cite news|title=Rogers reaches 12-year broadcast deal with NHL worth $5.2-billion|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/rogers-reaches-12-year-broadcast-deal-with-nhl-worth-52-billion/article15600412/|work=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=November 26, 2013|location=Toronto|date=November 27, 2013}}</ref><ref name=cbcnews-rogersnhl>{{cite news|title=Rogers scores national NHL TV rights for $5.2B|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/rogers-scores-national-nhl-tv-rights-for-5-2b-1.2440645|work=CBC News|accessdate=November 26, 2013}}</ref><ref name=torstar-hugeblow>{{cite news|title=NHL deal with Rogers a huge blow to TSN and CBC: Mudhar|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/hockey/2013/11/26/nhl_deal_with_rogers_a_huge_blow_to_tsn_and_cbc_mudhar.html|work=Toronto Star|accessdate=November 26, 2013|date=November 26, 2013}}</ref><ref name=cbcsports-rogers14>{{cite news|title=CBC partners with Rogers in landmark NHL rights deal|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/nhl/cbc-partners-with-rogers-in-landmark-nhl-rights-deal-1.2440326|work=CBC Sports|accessdate=November 26, 2013}}</ref><ref name=gandm-hnicnewgame>{{cite news|last1=Bradshaw|first1=James|title=Rogers' Hockey Night in Canada will be a whole new game for viewers|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/hockey/canadians-prepare-for-more-game-coverage-storytelling-with-new-nhl-season/article20930976/?page=all|accessdate=October 12, 2014|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>\n[[File:Sportsnet Mobile Studio in Regina.jpg|thumb|A [[Sportsnet]] mobile studio in [[Regina, Saskatchewan|Regina]] during [[Sportsnet]]'s ''Rogers Hometown Hockey'' tour]]\nUnder a sub-licensing agreement with Rogers, [[Quebecor Media]] holds national [[French language|French-language]] rights to the NHL, with all coverage airing on its specialty channel [[TVA Sports]]. TVA Sports' flagship broadcasts on Saturday nights focus primarily on the [[Montreal Canadiens]].<ref name=nhl-tvasports>{{cite web|title=NHL, TVA Sports launch French-language agreement|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=729553|website=NHL.com|accessdate=21 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=torstar-rogersnhl14>{{cite news|title=NHL signs 12-year TV, Internet deal with Rogers; CBC keeps \u2018Hockey Night in Canada\u2019|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/hockey/2013/11/26/nhl_signs_12year_broadcast_deal_with_rogers_cbc_keeps_hockey_night_in_canada.html|work=Toronto Star|accessdate=November 26, 2013|date=November 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nRogers sought to increase the prominence of NHL content on digital platforms by re-launching the NHL's digital [[out-of-market sports package]] GameCentre Live as Rogers NHL GameCentre Live, adding the ability to stream all of Rogers' national NHL telecasts, along with in-market streaming of regional games for teams whose regional rights are held by Sportsnet.<ref name=np-everygame>{{cite news|title=Rogers will allow you to watch even more NHL games online this season \u2026 just not all of them|url=http://sports.nationalpost.com/2014/09/03/how-rogers-will-allow-you-to-watch-even-more-nhl-games-online-this-season-just-not-all-of-them/|accessdate=September 18, 2014|work=National Post|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140918202857/http://sports.nationalpost.com/2014/09/03/how-rogers-will-allow-you-to-watch-even-more-nhl-games-online-this-season-just-not-all-of-them/|archivedate=September 18, 2014}}</ref> ''GamePlus''\u2014an additional mode featuring alternate camera angles intended for a [[second screen]] experience, such as angles focusing on certain players, net and referee cameras, and a Skycam in selected venues, was also added exclusively for GameCentre Live subscribers who are subscribed to Rogers' cable, internet, or wireless services.<ref name=globeandmail-advisor>{{cite news|title=How do you like your hockey? Rogers, NHL want to find out|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/industry-news/marketing/how-do-you-watch-hockey-rogers-nhl-launch-listening-tour-to-find-out/article16695957/|accessdate=July 15, 2014|work=The Globe & Mail|date=February 4, 2014}}</ref><ref name=gandm-gameplus>{{cite web|title=Rogers GamePlus has NHL angles covered, but app will come at a price|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/hockey/rogers-gameplus-has-nhl-angles-covered-but-app-will-come-at-a-price/article20958049/|website=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=October 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the lead-up to the 2014-15 season, Rogers began to promote its networks as the new home of the NHL through a multi-platform advertising campaign; the campaign featured advertising and cross-promotions across Rogers' properties, such as [[The Shopping Channel]], which began to feature presentations of NHL merchandise, and its parenting magazine ''[[Today's Parent]]'', which began to feature hockey-themed stories in its issues.<ref name=globeandmail-adbuys>{{cite news|title=Rogers ramps up NHL ad buys|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/industry-news/marketing/rogers-ramps-up-nhl-ad-buys/article19479990/|accessdate=July 15, 2014|work=The Globe & Mail|date=July 6, 2014}}</ref> On May 28, 2014, Rogers announced a six-year sponsorship deal with [[Scotiabank]], which saw the bank become the title sponsor for ''Wednesday Night Hockey'' and ''[[Hockey Day in Canada]]'', and become a sponsor for other segments and initiatives throughout Rogers' NHL coverage.<ref name=torstar-scotiabank>{{cite web|title=Rogers and Scotiabank reach NHL sponsorship deal|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2014/05/28/rogers_and_scotiabank_reach_nhl_sponsorship_deal.html|work=Toronto Star|accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn October 6, 2014, Rogers and NHL began their media sales venture in which Rogers will lead all Canadian national NHL media sales across its owned and operated broadcast and digital platforms as well as ad sales for League-owned digital assets in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=733209|title=NHL and Rogers announce media sales partnership|work=NHL.com}}</ref>\n\n==Digital products and services==\n===OutRank by Rogers===\n<!-- The page [[OutRank by Rogers]] redirects here. -->\n\nIn 2011, a partnership was formed between Rogers Communications and [[Yodle, Inc]] to provide a suite of digital marketing services to Canadian small, medium, and enterprise size business.<ref>{{cite web|title=Multi-Location: ONE Solution|url=http://www.rogersoutrank.com/national-brands|publisher=Outrank by Rogers|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Thomas|first1=Ryan|title=Why Most Renovations Start In The Kitchen And What Homeowners Might Be Missing|url=https://online.wsj.com/article/PR-CO-20130507-912991.html|publisher=[[Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=30 September 2014|quote=OutRank by Rogers helps small businesses connect with potential customers.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Yodle Shows Strong Momentum in a Record-Breaking 2012|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/press-release/20130211/yodle-shows-strong-momentum-record-breaking-2012-1075556|accessdate=17 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Getting customers, a keyword at a time|url=http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=391edc09-d5a2-478a-9b4e-7f76a5771101|publisher=[[Vancouver Sun]]|accessdate=17 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Why Most Renovations Start In The Kitchen And What Homeowners Might Be Missing|url=https://online.wsj.com/article/PR-CO-20130507-912991.html|publisher=[[Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=17 October 2014}}</ref> These solutions have been deployed under the name OutRank by Rogers and operate as a business unit within the company. Services include [[search engine optimization]], [[mobile marketing]], [[social media marketing]], [[pay per click]], and [[analytics]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Arellano|first1=Nestor|title=Rogers targets small biz with new online marketing suite|url=http://www.itbusiness.ca/news/rogers-targets-small-biz-with-new-online-marketing-suite/16907|quote=Called Outrank, the service promises to help companies generate more inbound phone calls and emails by offering a suite of products that include Web site design, search engine optimization (SEO) services, campaign tracking and paid search marketing.|publisher=[[ITBusiness]]|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Roseman|first1=Ellen|title=Refunds can be elusive without media help: Roseman|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/personal_finance/2013/12/06/refunds_can_be_elusive_without_media_help_roseman.html|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=mobile1>{{cite web|last1=Atchison|first1=Chris|title=Creating a Mobile Website|url=http://www.connectedforbusiness.ca/business/creating-a-mobile-website/|publisher=Connected for Business|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Condron|first1=Frank|title=Don\u2019t Ignore Online Customers|url=http://www.profitguide.com/news/don%E2%80%99t-let-your-online-presence-miss-out-48473|publisher=[[Profit (magazine)|Profit]]|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref> The opening was announced in January 2012 with the launch of their first client, Ontario-based CLS Roofing.<ref>{{cite web|last=Laermer|first=Emily|title=Online marketer Yodle expanding into Canada|url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20120119/SMALLBIZ/120119863|work=Crain's New York Business|publisher=Crain Communications Inc.}}</ref> OutRank by Rogers is a Google Premier SMB Partner and promotes [[Responsive web design|responsive]] web design.<ref>{{cite web|title=Find a Premier SMB Partner to help grow your business|url=https://www.google.ca/intl/en/ads/premiersmbpartner/advertisers-findpartner.html|publisher=[[Google]]|accessdate=17 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=OutRank by Rogers' Small Business Customers See 60% Rise in Web Traffic From Mobile Devices|url=http://www.advfn.com/news_OutRank-by-Rogers-Small-Business-Customers-See-60_56169361.html|accessdate=17 October 2014}}</ref> The company is a donor to the [[Ronald McDonald House Charities Canada#Toronto|Ronald Mcdonald House of Toronto]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Home for Dinner Photos - Outrank by Rogers|url=http://rmhtoronto.org/Home-for-Dinner-Photos-Outrank-by-Rogers|publisher=[[Ronald McDonald House Charities]]|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Zoocasa===\nIn 2008, Rogers Communications launched '''Zoocasa''', an online real estate listing service. The company later became a licensed real estate brokerage and in May 2013, the website relaunched to allow homebuyers to find properties and agents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/real_estate/2015/06/09/rogers-shuts-down-discount-brokerage-zoocasa.html|title=Rogers shuts down discount brokerage Zoocasa {{!}} Toronto Star|website=thestar.com|access-date=2016-10-16}}</ref> The service also provided rebates on real estate commissions to buyers and sellers. Zoocasa was shut down on June 22, 2015. The website's domain and technology were purchased for $350,000 and the website relaunched on July 2, 2015 under new ownership.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/real_estate/2015/07/02/rogers-communications-sells-zoocasa-real-estate-site.html|title=Rogers Communications sells Zoocasa real estate site {{!}} Toronto Star|website=thestar.com|accessdate=2016-10-16}}</ref>\n\n=== Texture ===\n[[Texture (app)|Texture]] (previously known as Next Issue) was a digital magazine app introduced to the Canadian market by Rogers in 2013.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/rogers-new-magazine-app-caters-to-digital-reading-habits/article26599368/|title=Rogers revamps Next Issue app to cater to digital reading habits|last=Bradshaw|first=James|date=30 September 2015|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|access-date=24 December 2017}}</ref> The service had a monthly subscription fee that gave readers access to over 200 magazines in English and French.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.texture.ca/en/newsstand/|title=Texture Canada Catalog|access-date=24 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nTexture was purchased by Apple in 2018 and the service discontinued in 2019 in favor of [[Apple News+]].\n\n=== Rogers Bank ===\n'''Rogers Bank''' ({{lang-fr|Banque Rogers}}) is a Canadian [[financial services]] company wholly owned by Rogers Communications. Rogers applied to the [[Minister of Finance (Canada)|Minister of Finance]] under the ''[[Bank Act (Canada)|Bank Act]]'' for permission to establish a Schedule I bank (a domestic bank that may accept deposits) in summer 2011.<ref>{{cite news| title=Broadcaster, Internet Provider, Wireless Carrier .. Bank?| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2013/09/07/rogers-credit-card_n_3882710.html| accessdate=2 April 2017|work=[[The Huffington Post]]}}</ref> At launch, Rogers Bank offered a Rogers-branded [[credit card]] targeted at existing customers.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://business.financialpost.com/2013/05/03/rogers-gets-closer-to-starting-banking-business/| title=Rogers gets closer to starting banking business| newspaper=[[Financial Post]]| last=Dobby| first=Christine| date=2013-05-03| accessdate=2013-09-23}}</ref> A companion card branded for Rogers subsidiary [[Fido Solutions|Fido]] was introduced in 2016.<ref>{{cite news| last1=Behar| first1=Rose| title=Fido launches travel-friendly cash back MasterCard through Rogers Bank| url=https://mobilesyrup.com/2016/07/28/fido-launches-travel-friendly-cash-back-mastercard-through-rogers-bank/| accessdate=November 13, 2017| work=MobileSyrup| date=July 28, 2016}}</ref> The bank offers three categories of credit card to Canadians: Fido [[Mastercard]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://financefeat.com/rogers-mastercard/|title=Review: Rogers MasterCard Credit Cards|date=2019-03-13|website=Financefeat|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref> Rogers Platinum Mastercard,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://financefeat.com/rogers-platinum-mastercard/|title=Review: Rogers Platinum MasterCard Credit Card|date=2019-03-15|website=Financefeat|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref> and Rogers World Elite Mastercard.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://financefeat.com/rogers-world-elite-mastercard/|title=Review: Rogers World Elite Mastercard Credit Card|date=2019-03-18|website=Financefeat|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Canada|Companies}}\n*[[Media ownership in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Rogers Communications}}\n* {{official website|https://www.rogers.com/}}\n\n{{Rogers Communications}}\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Telecommunications}}\n{{Internet service providers of Canada}}\n{{S&P/TSX 60}}\n{{Major telecommunications companies}}\n{{Canadian banks}}\n{{NHL}}\n{{Toronto Blue Jays owners}}\n{{MLBOwners}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:1960 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies established in 1960]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Toronto Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Rogers Communications| ]]\n[[Category:Toronto Blue Jays owners]]\n[[Category:Canadian brands]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies established in 1960]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1960]]\n", "name_user": "Blairall", "label": "safe", "comment": "revised a link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rogers_Communications"}
{"title_page": "Blair Waldorf", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color     = #F0E68C\n| name      = Blair Bablilonious Waldorf\n| series    = [[Gossip Girl (novel series)|Gossip Girl]]\n| image     = GGBlaircover.jpg\n| alt       = A brunette, female model in a dress\n| caption   = Blair as portrayed on the cover of ''It Had To Be You''\n| first     = '''Novel''': <br>''[[Gossip Girl (novel series)#Gossip Girl|Gossip Girl]]'' <br>'''Television''': <br>\"[[Pilot (Gossip Girl)|Pilot]]\" <br>(episode 1.01)\n| last      = '''Novel''': <br> ''[[Gossip Girl (novel series)#Gossip Girl|I Will Always Love You]]''  <br>'''Television''': <br>\"[[New York, I Love You XOXO]]\" <br>(episode 6.10)\n| creator   = '''Character''' <br>[[Cecily von Ziegesar]] <br>'''Television producers''' <br>[[Josh Schwartz]] <br>[[Stephanie Savage]]\n| portrayer = [[Leighton Meester]]\n| full_name = Blair Cornelia Waldorf\n| alias     = B, Queen B, gossip girl, Manhattan Hotty\n| spouse    = '''Television''': <br>[[Chuck Bass|Charles \"Chuck\" \u201cChuckster\u201d \u201cchuckisimo\u201d \u201cchucko\u201d chuchorino\u201d Bass of the Manhattan(upper east west sider) sea basses]] <br>(husband/lover) <br>[[List of Gossip Girl characters#Louis Grimaldi|Prince Louis Grimaldi]] <br>(ex-husband)\n| title     = '''Television:''' <br>Princess Blair of Monaco de country in za-Europe <br>(during her marriage to [[List of Gossip Girl characters#Louis Grimaldi|Louis]])\n| family    = [[List of Gossip Girl characters#Harold Waldorf|Harold]] and [[List of Gossip Girl characters#Eleanor Waldorf|Eleanor Waldorf]]<br>(parents) <br>[[List of Gossip Girl characters#Cyrus Rose|Cyrus Rose]] <br>(stepfather) <br>[[List of Gossip Girl characters#Guest stars|Aaron Rose]]<br>(stepbrother) <br>'''Novels:''' <br>Tyler Waldorf<br>(younger brother) <br>Ying and Yang Waldorf<br>(adoptive sister and brother)<br>Yale Waldorf-Rose <br>(half-sister)\n| children  = '''Television''':<br>Henry Bass <br>(son, with Chuck; [[New York, I Love You XOXO|flash-forward]])\n}}\n'''Blair Cornelia Waldorf'''<!-- Please do not add a name from the TV series --><ref>von Ziegesar, ''Gossip Girl: I Will Always Love You'', p. 336</ref> is one of the main characters of ''[[Gossip Girl (novel series)|Gossip Girl]]'',<ref>{{cite news |first=James |last=Morrison |coauthors= |title=Protests at sex and drugs in teen publishing sensation |work=arlindo-correia.org |page= |date=August 25, 2002 |accessdate=December 2, 2010 |url=http://www.arlindo-correia.org/120103.html}}</ref> introduced in the original series of novels and also appearing in the [[Gossip Girl|television]] and [[comic]] adaptations. Described as \"a girl of extremes\" by creator [[Cecily von Ziegesar]],<ref>{{cite news|title=A Sheepish Interview with Cecily von Ziegesar |work=sheepishfashionista.com |date=October 5, 2010 |accessdate=December 2, 2010 |url=http://sheepishfashionista.com/2010/10/05/sheepish-interview-with-cecily-von-ziegesar-inspired-creator-original-gossip-girl/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110120224442/http://sheepishfashionista.com/2010/10/05/sheepish-interview-with-cecily-von-ziegesar-inspired-creator-original-gossip-girl/ |archivedate=January 20, 2011 }}</ref> she is a [[New York City]] socialite and a comical overachiever who possesses both snobbish and sensitive sides. Due to her position as [[Queen bee (subculture)|queen bee]] of [[Manhattan]]'s social scene, Blair's actions and relations are under constant scrutiny from the mysterious Gossip Girl, a popular [[blog]]ger.\n\n[[Leighton Meester]], who portrayed the character in the television drama, has described Blair as being insecure about her social status.<ref>{{cite news|title=''Gossip Girl'' Actress Spills the Beans on Her Character|work=buddytv.com|date=September 25, 2007|accessdate=October 9, 2008|url=http://www.buddytv.com/articles/gossip-girl/gossip-girl-the-new-cw-11418.aspx|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414201116/http://www.buddytv.com/articles/gossip-girl/gossip-girl-the-new-cw-11418.aspx|archive-date=2015-04-14|url-status=dead}}</ref> At times, this anxiety creates flaws and complexities which contribute to character development. In Meester's view, the true Blair is ultimately a good girl at heart.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Duck |first=Siobhan |url=http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/story/0,23739,22943161-5003422,00.html |title=Queen bee is really a good girl |publisher= The Courier-Mail |date=2007-12-20 |work=news.com.au |access-date=2020-04-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071220221828/http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/story/0,23739,22943161-5003422,00.html |archive-date=December 20, 2007}}</ref>\n\nBlair has been compared to vintage film and literary figures, including [[Becky Sharp (character)|Becky Sharp]] and [[The Eustace Diamonds|Lizzie Eustace]]. She is commonly likened to Lila Fowler of Francine Pascal's ''[[Sweet Valley High]]'' series.<ref name=fowler=one>{{cite news |first=Amelia |last=McDonell-Parry |coauthors= |title=Casting the ''Sweet Valley High'' Movie |work=[[ABC News]] |page= |date=November 25, 2011 |accessdate=September 1, 2018 |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/sweet-valley-high-movie/story?id=15016223}}</ref><ref name=fowler-two>{{cite news |first=Zara |last=Husaini |coauthors= |title=Creating the ''Sweet Valley High'' Cast of My Dreams |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |page= |date=January 25, 2014 |accessdate=September 1, 2018 |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/zara-husaini/casting-and-styling-the-s_b_4298331.html}}</ref> Meester's portrayal has also drawn comparisons to roles played by [[Joan Collins]] and [[Audrey Hepburn]]. She is the most critically acclaimed character of the franchise, while the television character has drawn real-life attention surrounding fashion and her love life.\n\n==Character in print==\n''[[Gossip Girl (novel series)|Gossip Girl]]'' is a series of novels about socially prominent young adults in [[New York City]]. The story primarily follows Blair Waldorf and her best friend [[Serena van der Woodsen]] during their years in high school and college. Due to her fame on the [[Upper East Side]], Blair is featured on the website of \"Gossip Girl,\" an anonymous gossip [[blog]]ger whose posts appear occasionally throughout the story.\n\n===Novel series===\nIn the first book, Blair is introduced as a privileged, comically vain overachiever.<ref name=NYreview>{{cite news |first=Janet |last=Malcolm |coauthors= |title=The Wicked Joy of the ''Gossip Girl'' Novels |work=[[The New Yorker]] |page= |date=March 10, 2008 |accessdate=July 9, 2009 |url=http://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/atlarge/2008/03/10/080310crat_atlarge_malcolm}}</ref> She is described as an alluring brunette,<ref name=Blair>{{cite news |first=Cecily |last=von Ziegesar |coauthors= |title=''It Had To Be You: The Gossip Girl Prequel'' |work=Poppy (Little, Brown and Company) |page= |year=2009 |accessdate=July 12, 2011 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NF6T9CbK7h0C&printsec=frontcover&dq=It+Had+To+Be+You+Gossip+Girl#v=snippet&q=two%20hottest&f=false}}</ref> and occasionally models her appearance and demeanor after famous actresses, including [[Marilyn Monroe]] and, most often, [[Audrey Hepburn]].<ref>von Ziegesar, ''Gossip Girl: Because I'm Worth It'', p. 36</ref> In early novels, the character is also written as [[Bulimia nervosa|bulimic]].\n\nBlair is largely motivated by matters surrounding family, romance, and ambition. However, her tendency to overachieve can lead to feelings of paranoia, with dramatic or comical results. In a review for ''[[The New Yorker]]'', Janet Malcolm remarked that Blair's issues made her \"both a broader caricature and a more real person\" than the other ''Gossip Girl'' characters.<ref name=NYreview/> In a 2009 interview, ''Gossip Girl'' creator [[Cecily von Ziegesar]] claimed to identify with Blair the most, stating, \"She is so unpredictable and dramatic. Such a bitch, but we understand why she is a bitch and we like her anyway\".<ref name=qa>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Hon \u00e4r en s\u00e5n bitch |work=aftonbladet.se |page= |date=March 26, 2009 |accessdate=July 16, 2011 |url=http://www.aftonbladet.se/nojesbladet/article4748648.ab?service=print}}</ref>\n\n====Story lines====\nThroughout most of the series' run, Blair grapples with a number of changes within her family. One year prior to the opening novel, Blair's parents divorced after her father ran off with another man. When her mother remarries, and her father leaves the country, Blair has difficulty accepting her stepfather, Cyrus Rose. In addition, her stress over these matters occasionally affects her other relationships.<ref>von Ziegesar, ''You Know You Love Me: A Gossip Girl Novel'', p. 30</ref> However, Blair ultimately remains close to her father Harold, who she often turns to for comfort.<ref>von Ziegesar, ''You Know You Love Me: A Gossip Girl Novel'', p. 3</ref> By contrast, she maintains a somewhat tenser relationship with her mother Eleanor. It is also revealed that Blair has struggled with [[bulimia]].<ref>von Ziegesar, ''Gossip Girl: Because I'm Worth It'', p. 81</ref>\n\nIn the opening novel, Blair learns of an affair between her friend Serena and her boyfriend Nate. This marks the beginning of the story's primary [[love triangle]], which recurs throughout the series.<ref>{{cite news |first=Shannon |last=Maughan |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Got Legs |work=[[Publishers Weekly]] |page= |date=May 11, 2007 |accessdate=November 30, 2015 |url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/new-titles/adult-announcements/article/1412-gossip-girl-s-got-legs.html}}</ref> Blair's romantic life has various effects on her character development. After Nate repeatedly hurts her, she eventually refuses to take him back until she believes in his ability to commit to her.<ref>{{cite news |first=Cecily |last=von Ziegesar |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl: I Will Always Love You'' \"The Honest Truth and Other Rewards\" |work=Poppy (Little, Brown and Company) |page= |year=2009 |accessdate=July 23, 2011 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=md8WgIIJjSUC&q=four+months+ago#v=snippet&q=four%20months%20ago&f=false}}</ref> In pursuing Nate, however, Blair herself cheats on her new boyfriend Pete, which results in her losing both of them.<ref>{{cite news |first=Cecily |last=von Ziegesar |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl: I Will Always Love You'' |work=Poppy (Little, Brown and Company) |page= |year=2009 |accessdate=July 23, 2011 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=md8WgIIJjSUC&q=love+triangle+Pete#v=snippet&q=love%20triangle%20Pete&f=false}}</ref> She eventually begins to acknowledge her mistakes, with her father's help.<ref name=IWA>{{cite news |first=Cecily |last=von Ziegesar |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl: I Will Always Love You'' |work=Poppy (Little, Brown and Company) |page= |year=2009 |accessdate=July 12, 2011 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=md8WgIIJjSUC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Gossip+Girl:+I+Will+Always+Love+You#v=onepage&q=Harold&f=false}}</ref> She later grows closer to [[Chuck Bass]] (which initially occurred in the series' television adaptation), who she'd previously known for years, which leads them to briefly date one another.<ref name=IWA/>\n\nBlair is noted for an over-achieving nature, which often appears in humorous scenes. In a review for ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine, [[Emily Nussbaum]] lauded one of Blair's fantasies, which involves \"joining the Peace Corps, getting a killer tan, winning the Nobel Peace Prize, and having dinner with the president, 'who would then write her a recommendation to [[Yale University|Yale]], and then Yale would fall all over themselves to accept her.' \"<ref name=nyarticle>{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Nussbaum |authorlink=Emily Nussbaum |title=Psst, Serena is a slut. Pass it on |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |page= |date=May 21, 2005 |accessdate=July 12, 2011 |url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/arts/books/12058/}}</ref> ''The New Yorker''{{'s}} Janet Malcolm remarked that unlike some of her forerunners in film and literature, \"Blair already has all the money and position anyone could want. She is pure naked striving, restlessly seeking an object, any object, and never knowing when enough is enough.\"<ref name=NYreview/>\n\nBlair encounters a setback during her interview at Yale by revealing the recent stress in her life, and then kissing her interviewer on the cheek upon dismissal. Her father then makes a donation to the school, though Blair is still wait-listed.<ref>{{cite news |first=Cecily |last=von Ziegesar |coauthors= |title=''All I Want Is Everything: A Gossip Girl Novel'' |work=Poppy (Little, Brown and Company) |page= |year=2003 |accessdate=July 12, 2011 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qEE8K98qfkQC&pg=PA5&dq=Gossip+Girl+Yale+donate#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> In the twelfth book, ''I Will Always Love You'', it is revealed that she has been admitted to the university.<ref>von Ziegesar, ''Gossip Girl: I Will Always Love You'', p. 9</ref>\n\nIn addition to her feelings for Nate, Blair is sometimes said to feel competitive with Serena in other areas, including matters of beauty and popularity.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Cecily von Ziegesar Biography |work=bookrags.com |page= |date= |accessdate=July 16, 2011 |url=http://www.bookrags.com/biography/cecily-von-ziegesar-aya/}}</ref> This also leads to an occasional envy on Blair's part.<ref name=nyarticle/> It is unclear how much of Blair's perception of Serena is in line with reality; the narrative describes both characters as \"hands down the two hottest girls on the Upper East Side, and maybe all of Manhattan, or even the whole world.\"<ref name=Blair/>\n\n===Manga series===\n[[File:MangaBWaldorf.jpg|thumb|130px|right|alt=A manga drawing of Blair Waldorf|Blair as she appears in the manga.]]\nIn 2010, [[Yen Press]] began publishing a [[manga]] adaptation titled ''Gossip Girl: For Your Eyes Only'', written and illustrated by HyeKyung Baek. This series adapts notable scenarios from the novel\u2014including the triangle with Nate and Serena\u2014but also features new material.\n\nAfter losing her position as queen bee, Blair attempts to regain her former status while adjusting to a less privileged lifestyle.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gossip Girl: The Manga, Vol. 2|work=hachettebookgroup.com|accessdate=July 30, 2011|url=http://www.hachettebookgroup.com/books_9780759530270.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110323221422/http://www.hachettebookgroup.com/books_9780759530270.htm|archive-date=2011-03-23|url-status=dead}}</ref> In addition to this series, Blair also appears in a manga adaptation of the novel ''Gossip Girl: Psycho Killer'', a parody of horror stories.<ref>{{cite news |first=Kat |last=Rosenfield |title=''Gossip Girl: Psycho Killer'' Special Edition Manga: EXCLUSIVE First Look! |work=mtv.com |date=July 25, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011 |url=http://hollywoodcrush.mtv.com/2011/07/25/gossip-girl-psycho-killer-exclusive/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208070552/http://hollywoodcrush.mtv.com/2011/07/25/gossip-girl-psycho-killer-exclusive/ |archivedate=February 8, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Television series==\nIn 2007, ''Gossip Girl'' was [[Gossip Girl|adapted for television]]. According to Cecily von Ziegesar, the television character is largely faithful to the original.<ref name=qa/> Among the aspects to be maintained are her admiration for Audrey Hepburn and her interest in Yale University. However, the series is also noted for its deviations from the source material,<ref name=NYreview/> including the exclusion of Blair's brother Tyler. The show also explores romances between Blair and multiple male leads, resulting in occasional love triangles. In the fifth season, Blair is revealed to be pregnant with Prince of Monaco, Louis Grimaldi's child. However the child later dies before birth after a car crash Blair and Chuck were in.<ref name=child>{{cite news |first= Dawn|last= Fallik|coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'' Season 5, Episode 1, 'Yes, Then Zero': TV Recap |work=The Wall Street Journal |page= |date=September 26, 2011 |accessdate=September 27, 2011 |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2011/09/26/gossip-girl-season-5-episode-1-yes-then-zero-tv-recap/}}</ref>\n\nAmong fans and the media, Blair's bond with Chuck Bass was commonly known by the portmanteau \"Chair\", while her relationship with Dan Humphrey was referred to as \"Dair\". The nicknames and viewer interest in these relationships were recognized by the show's producers.<ref>{{cite news |first=Vlada |last=Gelman |coauthors= |title=Gossip Girl Boss Previews Blair and Her Men, Serena's New Life, and Exploiting the UES\n |work=tvline.com |page= |date=September 1, 2011 |accessdate=September 13, 2011 |url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/09/gossip-girl-season-5-preview-josh-safran/}}</ref>\n \n===Casting===\n\n{{quote|They were like, 'Be bitchy and nice, ugly and pretty, young and old, stupid and smart, innocent and slutty, blond and brunette. Can you be all those things?'|4=Leighton Meester <ref>{{cite news|first=Jason |last=Gay |title=Dirty Pretty Things |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=November 23, 2010 |url=http://chaceconline.com/press/news.php?newsid=63 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120707050057/http://chaceconline.com/press/news.php?newsid=63 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 7, 2012 }}</ref>}}\n\nTo prepare for the part of Blair, actress [[Leighton Meester]], a natural blonde, dyed her hair brown before auditioning, and also studied the first novel.<ref name=peoplebio>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Leighton Meester biography |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |page= |date=November 25, 2008 |accessdate=September 27, 2009 |url=http://www.people.com/people/leighton_meester/biography}}</ref><ref name=ctv>{{cite news |first=Tyrone |last=Warner |coauthors= |title=Leighton Meester won't let ''Gossip Girl'' fans down |work=ctv.ca |page= |date= |accessdate=October 9, 2008 |url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/show/CTVShows/20071031/gg_meester_interview_071031/20071101/}}</ref> She has described the character as multi-faceted, labeling her \"a little bit of everything which is pretty amazing.\"<ref name=ctv/> Like von Ziegesar, Meester has also claimed to relate to Blair on certain levels. Prior to the show's debut in 2007, the actress stated that, \"The only way to play Blair, or any character, and make her human, is to find what she is inside me. And I know I have my insecurities, too.\" She went on to say that, \"The way Blair and I are ''not'' alike when it comes to insecurities is: ''She'' pays ''so'' much attention to hers!\"<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Leighton Meester: rich on 'Gossip Girl' |work=[[Associated Press]] |page= |date=September 12, 2007 |accessdate=August 11, 2010 |url=http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/Entertainment/20070912/leighton_gossip_070912/}}</ref> Meester's casting was described by ''[[Yahoo!]]'' as a star-making role which moved her \"into the pop culture vanguard,\"<ref name=YahooReview>{{cite news |title=Leighton Meester |work=[[Yahoo!]] |page= |date= |accessdate=July 9, 2009|url=https://tv.yahoo.com/leighton-meester/contributor/713039}}</ref> while Cecily von Ziegesar has called her a perfect choice.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jocelyn |last=Vena |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'' Author Is A 'Faithful Watcher' Of The TV Series |work=[[MTV]] |page= |date=October 16, 2008 |accessdate=October 4, 2009 |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1597121/20081015/index.jhtml}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, Meester revealed plans to leave the show in 2012. ''[[E!]] Online'' and other outlets speculated that her departure would possibly mark the end of the series.<ref name=Announcement>{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Malkin |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'': Getting Ready to End? |work=[[E!]] |page= |date=December 13, 2010 |accessdate=December 12, 2012 |url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/marc_malkin/b215864_gossip_girl_getting_ready_end.html}}</ref>\n\n===Season 1===\n{{Main|List of Gossip Girl episodes}}\n[[File:BWaldorf lead.jpg|thumb|170px|right|alt=Screenshot of Leighton Meester in 'Gossip Girl'|Blair as she appears in the TV adaptation, portrayed by Leighton Meester.]]\nIn {{nowrap|Season 1}} of ''Gossip Girl'', Blair is introduced as the Upper East Side's beautiful and popular [[Queen bee (sociology)|queen bee]]. She is the daughter of Eleanor Waldorf, a famous fashion designer. She is dating Nate Archibald, and is best friends with Serena van der Woodsen. She also finds a close companion in Nate's best friend and her childhood friend Chuck Bass, who becomes a partner for her schemes. When Serena returns home from boarding school, Blair learns from Nate that he lost his virginity to a drunken Serena over a year ago.<ref>{{cite news|title=''Gossip Girl'': \"The Wild Bunch\" |work=cwtv.com |accessdate=July 16, 2011 |url=http://www.cwtv.com/shows/gossip-girl/episodes/101 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110824071609/http://www.cwtv.com/shows/gossip-girl/episodes/101 |archivedate=August 24, 2011 }}</ref> Blair retaliates by publicly revealing Serena's connection to a rehab hospital. She then learns that the actual patient is Serena's younger brother, Eric, who had been committed after a suicide attempt. Afterward, a remorseful Blair reconciles with Serena.<ref>{{cite news|title=''Gossip Girl'': \"Poison Ivy\" |work=cwtv.com |accessdate=July 16, 2011 |url=http://www.cwtv.com/shows/gossip-girl/episodes/102 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110828065358/http://www.cwtv.com/shows/gossip-girl/episodes/102 |archivedate=August 28, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'' Rundown: Episode 3, \"Poison Ivy\" |work=buzzsugar.com |page= |date=October 7, 2011 |accessdate=July 16, 2011 |url=http://www.buzzsugar.com/Gossip-Girl-Rundown-Episode-3-Poison-Ivy-676065}}</ref>\n\nAfter learning that Nate no longer loves her, Blair sleeps with Chuck, eventually falling for him. This leads to a heated affair and an eventual love triangle. Her inability to choose creates much of the first season's story line.<ref>{{cite news|title=''Gossip Girl'': \"Hi, Society\" |work=cwtv.com |accessdate=July 16, 2011 |url=http://www.cwtv.com/shows/gossip-girl/episodes/109 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120122213350/http://www.cwtv.com/shows/gossip-girl/episodes/109 |archivedate=January 22, 2012 }}</ref> There are brief mentions of Blair's past struggle with anorexia-bulimia that are never mentioned again past the first season.\n\nShe also begins a brief power struggle with freshman [[Jenny Humphrey]]. After she unites with Chuck and Nate in order to save Serena from the scheming [[Georgina Sparks]], Chuck realizes that his feelings for Blair are real and suggests that they spend the summer together in Tuscany. However, he is discouraged by his father at the last minute, and stands Blair up.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Gossip Girl Recap: Episode 18, \"Much 'I Do' About Nothing\" |work=buzzsugar.com |page= |date=May 20, 2008 |accessdate=July 16, 2011 |url=http://www.buzzsugar.com/Gossip-Girl-Recap-Episode-18-Much-I-Do-About-Nothing-1645841}}</ref>\n\n===Season 2===\nAt the launch of the second season, Blair was described by creators as the [[Queen (chess)|queen]] at the center of the ''Gossip Girl'' chess game.<ref name=pmagazine>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Scene Stealers: The TV Stars We Had to Watch |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |page= |date=November 25, 2008 |accessdate=September 25, 2009 |url=http://www.people.com/people/package/gallery/0,,20240653_20241971,00.html}}</ref> A large portion of her story line in {{nowrap|Season 2}} revolves around her love-hate relationship with Chuck Bass, which was labeled \"the heart of ''GG''\" by ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine.<ref name=peoplebio/> While competing with Serena, Blair forms an unexpected friendship with Jenny, who states that they each work for everything they achieve, while Serena often glides through life. During their interviews at Yale University, Blair and Serena apologize for their ill feelings and resume their friendship.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'': \"New Haven Can Wait\" |work=Zap2it |page= |date= |accessdate=July 9, 2009|url=http://tvlistings.zap2it.com/tv/gossip-girl-new-haven-can-wait/EP009322060026}}</ref>\n\nIn the episode \"O Brother, Where Bart Thou?\", Chuck is devastated by news of his father's death, prompting Blair to offer her support while telling Chuck that she loves him. He initially shuns her advances, but later turns to her for comfort.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'': \"O Brother, Where Bart Thou?\" |work=Zap2it |page= |date= |accessdate=July 9, 2009|url=http://tvlistings.zap2it.com/tv/gossip-girl-o-brother-where-bart-thou/EP009322060033}}</ref> However, the two stop seeing each other due to Chuck's uncle, Jack Bass, convincing him he has an inability to commit to a relationship.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'': \"Gone with the Will\" |work=Zap2it |page= |date= |accessdate=July 9, 2009|url=http://tvlistings.zap2it.com/tv/gossip-girl-gone-with-the-will/EP009322060035}}</ref> After being rejected by Yale, Blair finds unexpected encouragement from Nate.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'': \"The Grandfather\" |work=Zap2it |page= |date= |accessdate=July 9, 2009|url=http://tvlistings.zap2it.com/tv/gossip-girl-the-grandfather/EP009322060042}}</ref> She is later accepted into New York University, and her competitive relationship with Georgina is eventually renewed.\n\nAs the season ends, Blair crowns Jenny the new queen of Constance Billard School. In the season finale, it is discovered that Blair slept with Chuck's uncle Jack and that Chuck had slept with Vanessa Abrams. Chuck then departs for Europe. He later returns to New York and reconciles with Blair while declaring his love for her, and the two finally begin a committed relationship.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'': \"The Goodbye Gossip Girl\" |work=[[TV Guide]] |page= |date= |accessdate=July 9, 2009|url=http://www.tvguide.com/detail/tv-show.aspx?tvobjectid=288136&more=ucepisodelist&episodeid=11183383}}</ref>\n\n===Season 3===\nIn the third season, Blair joins Vanessa, Georgina, and Jenny's brother Dan at NYU.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'': \"Reversals of Fortune\" |work=Zap2it |page= |date= |accessdate=October 3, 2009|url=http://tvlistings.zap2it.com/tv/gossip-girl-reversals-of-fortune/EP009322060046}}</ref> Much of her story line concerns her inability to attain her previous status at her new school. She finds emotional support from her mother, as well as Chuck. However, she and Chuck separate once again when Blair feels that he manipulated her while competing with his uncle (Chuck made a deal with Jack that Blair could sleep with him and in exchange, Chuck gets his hotel back that Jack initially stole to 'destroy Chuck').\n\nShe later transfers to Columbia University, and learns that an emotionally reformed Chuck was responsible for her enrollment.<ref>{{cite news |first=Gonzalez |last=Sandra |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'' recap: Chuck and Blair save each other |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |page= |date=May 4, 2010 |accessdate=August 25, 2009 |url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2010/05/04/gossip-girl-recap-ep-20-dad-world/?xid=rss-feed-tvwatch-%27Gossip+Girl%27+recap%3A+Chuck+and+Blair+save+each+other}}</ref> They later team up as part of a role-playing scheme to help Serena's mother and Chuck's adopted mother, Lily. In the season finale, Chuck attempts to propose to Blair, but is interrupted by Dan, who reveals that Chuck had slept with Jenny. Two weeks later, Blair and Serena depart for Paris intending to spend the summer together.<ref>{{cite news\n |first=Mark\n |last=Estes\n |title=Gossip Girl 3.22 \"Last Tango, Then Paris\" Recap/Review\n |work=tvovermind.Zap2it.com\n |date=May 18, 2010\n |accessdate=July 16, 2011\n |url=http://tvovermind.zap2it.com/thecw/gossip-girl/gossip-girl-3-22-review/23886\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718151414/http://tvovermind.zap2it.com/thecw/gossip-girl/gossip-girl-3-22-review/23886\n |archivedate=July 18, 2011\n}}</ref>\n\n===Season 4===\nIn {{nowrap|Season 4,}} Blair and Chuck become competitive once again, but eventually resume their sexual relations before recognizing their love for one another. When the relationship interferes with their business interests, she and Chuck break up once more. Chuck promises he'll wait for her, and both affirm their belief that their love will reunite them in the end.<ref>{{cite news |first=Hillary |last=Busis |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'' Season 4, Episode 9 'The Witches of Bushwick' |work=The Wall Street Journal |page= |date=November 16, 2010 |accessdate=July 16, 2011 |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2010/11/16/gossip-girl-season-4-episode-9-the-witches-of-bushwick/}}</ref>\n\nBlair then teams up with Dan when the two share common goals. They also end up working together at ''W.'' magazine, where friction develops between the two.<ref name=DB>{{cite news |first=Tierney |last=Bricker |title=''Gossip Girl''{{'s}} Leighton Meester talks Dan and Blair: 'I think they're good for each other' |work=[[Zap2it]] |date=February 1, 2011 |accessdate=March 28, 2011 |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/02/gossip-girls-leighton-meester-talks-dan-and-blair-i-think-theyre-good-for-each-other.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110408165853/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/02/gossip-girls-leighton-meester-talks-dan-and-blair-i-think-theyre-good-for-each-other.html |archivedate=April 8, 2011 }}</ref> On Valentine's Day, she discovers that Chuck has romantic feelings for Raina Thorpe, the daughter of his business rival. Later, she and Dan spend the evening talking on their cell phones while watching ''[[Rosemary's Baby (film)|Rosemary's Baby]]''.<ref>{{cite news |first=Tierney |last=Bricker |title=''Gossip Girl''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s 'It-Girl Happened One Night': A Valentine's Day 'Dair' |work=Zap2it |date=February 15, 2011 |accessdate=July 16, 2011 |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/02/gossip-girls-it-girl-happened-one-night-a-valentines-day-dair.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110324032322/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/02/gossip-girls-it-girl-happened-one-night-a-valentines-day-dair.html |archivedate=March 24, 2011 }}</ref> Blair later quits ''W.'' and is shown asleep with Dan in his Brooklyn flat. Later, upon growing curious of their feelings for one another, Blair and Dan share a kiss before the mid-season hiatus.\n\nBlair eventually decides that she wants to be with Chuck, but shuns him once again after he tries to humiliate Dan.<ref>{{cite news |first=Tierney |last=Bricker |title=The aftermath of Dan and Blair's kiss |work=Zap2it |date=April 18, 2011 |accessdate=May 8, 2011 |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/04/gossip-girl-the-kids-stay-in-the-picture-the-aftermath-of-dan-and-blairs-kiss.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110423083429/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/04/gossip-girl-the-kids-stay-in-the-picture-the-aftermath-of-dan-and-blairs-kiss.html |archivedate=April 23, 2011 }}</ref> She is later courted by a prince from Monaco named Louis. During a private confrontation, a drunken Chuck punches a window after he finds out Prince Louis has proposed to Blair, which cuts Blair's face as it shatters. Afterward, Blair chooses to accept a proposal from Louis.<ref>{{cite news |first=Ashley |last=Ostlie |coauthors= |title=Gossip Girl Episode Recap: \"The Princesses and the Frog\" |work=TV Guide |page= |date=May 3, 2011 |accessdate=May 8, 2011 |url=http://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/gossip-girl-2011/episode-20-season-4/princesses-frog/288136}}</ref> Blair later attempts to warn Chuck about potential trouble in his family. She is then abducted by an enemy of the Basses, Raina's father Russell Thorpe. Chuck later rescues Blair and apologizes for his violent actions. Following a night out together, the two have sex before Chuck advises Blair to return to Louis, believing that she will be happier with him. However, the season ends with the revelation that Blair may be pregnant.<ref>{{cite news |first= Dawn|last= Fallik|coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'', 'The Wrong Goodbye,' Recap |work=The Wall Street Journal |page= |date=May 16, 2011 |accessdate=May 17, 2011 |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2011/05/16/gossip-girl-the-wrong-goodbye-season-4-episode-22-tv-recap/}}</ref>\n\n====Reaction to triangle====\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float: right; margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 2em; font-size: 85%; background:#c6dbf7; color:black; width:25em; max-width: 40%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |Chuck and Blair are always going to be connected in their way, and Dan and Serena are always going to be connected in their way. But that doesn't mean that there won't be new roads to go down that might be different than what we initially anticipated.\n\u2014Joshua Safran, producer<ref name=JS>{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |title=''Gossip Girl'' Boss on the Big Dan/Blair Smooch: 'It Was a Long Time Coming' |work=TV Line |page= |date=March 1, 2011 |accessdate=March 28, 2011 |url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/03/gossip-girl-dan-blair-spoilers-kiss/}}</ref>\n|}\n\nAmidst the fourth season, the romance between Dan and Blair became a polarizing topic among viewers<ref name=DB/> which also drew significant media interest. Jarett Wieselman of the ''[[New York Post]]'' applauded the development, feeling that Blair had \"more chemistry\" with Dan than with Chuck.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jarett |last=Wieselman |title=IM-ing about ''Gossip Girl'' |work=[[New York Post]] |date=March 1, 2011 |accessdate=March 28, 2011 |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/im_ing_about_gossip_girl_rgTaVdXB87fbszlthtUVnM |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110306192342/http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/im_ing_about_gossip_girl_rgTaVdXB87fbszlthtUVnM |archivedate=March 6, 2011 }}</ref> ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine's Chris Rovzar called Blair and Dan's story line \"believable\", citing their common ground in education and taste. Rovzar further stated, \"Since they live in a world where both only seem to have half a dozen real friends (if that), is it so crazy they'd end up together?\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Rovzar |title=How the Writers of ''Gossip Girl'' Sold Us on the Show's Most Unbelievable Couple |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |page= |date=March 8, 2011 |accessdate=March 28, 2011 |url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2011/03/how_the_writers_of_gossip_girl.html}}</ref> An article from ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' declared that \"Dan and Blair together are like Harry Burns and Sally Albright reincarnated \u2014 the couple was obviously inspired by ''[[When Harry Met Sally...]]''.\" It further commented that the couple paralleled Pacey and Joey's relationship from ''[[Dawson's Creek]]'' and concluded that Dan and Blair were \"the most inspired storyline and couple of the show\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Alfonso |last=Espina |title=The End of Gossip Girl: Chair vs. Dair |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |page= |date=December 19, 2012 |accessdate=September 8, 2016 |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/alfonso-espina/gossip-girl-finale_b_2324665.html}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' stated that Dan and Blair were like stars in an \"updated version of ''[[You've Got Mail]]''\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Tim |last=Stack |title=Gossip Girl recap: Dair to Get Closer |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |page= |date=February 15, 2011 |accessdate=September 8, 2016 |url=http://www.ew.com/recap/gossip-girl-season-4-episode-15/2}}</ref> Tierney Bricker of [[E!]] ranked all 25 ''Gossip Girl'' couples placing 'Dair' as the third best couple after Blair and Serena (#1) and 'Chair' (#2). Bricker stated that \"[Dan and Blair], out of all the main characters, were the most well-suited for each other. In real life, they would've been 'endgame'.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Tierney |last=Bricker |title=We Ranked All the Gossip Girl Couples and No. 1 May Surprise You |work=[[E!]] |page= |date=November 28, 2015 |accessdate=September 8, 2016 |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/719091/we-ranked-all-the-gossip-girl-couples-and-no-1-may-surprise-you}}</ref>\n\nDawn Fallik of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' was less positive, asserting that \"both characters have been so Blandified that there's no fun left in the show.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Dawn |last=Fallik |title=''Gossip Girl'' Season 4, Episode 17 'Empire of the Son': TV Recap |work=The Wall Street Journal |page= |date=February 28, 2011 |accessdate=March 28, 2011 |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2011/02/28/gossip-girl-season-4-episode-17-empire-of-the-son-tv-recap/}}</ref> A writer for ''E! Online''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Team WWK labeled the Dan/Blair relationship \"nomance nonsense\".<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |title=Spoiler Chat: Get Sweeps Scoop on Your Fave Gossip Girl, Glee and Grey's Anatomy Couples |work=E! |page= |date=May 11, 2011 |accessdate=July 16, 2011 |url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/watch_with_kristin/b235864_spoiler_chat_get_sweeps_scoop_on_your.html}}</ref>\n\nWith regard to Chuck and Blair, Meester stated, \"I can really relate to it\u2014not necessarily because it's this dramatic, tumultuous relationship, but because the way they love each other is very real, and not for the sake of being dramatic. It's actual love. There's nobody for each other but them.\"<ref>{{cite news |first= Katy|last= Hall|title=Leighton Meester In ''Allure'' |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |page= |date=December 14, 2010 |accessdate=December 14, 2010 |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/12/14/leighton-meester-in-allur_n_796354.html}}</ref> Meester also expressed fondness for Dan and Blair, however, stating, \"I think they're good for each other in a lot of ways, in a way that Chuck and Blair aren't.\"<ref name=DB/> Badgley claimed that he thought \"Blair [was] Dan's soul mate\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Karlis |last=Nicole |title=Penn Badgley Reveals: 'Blair Is Dan's Soul Mate'! |work=[[Hollywoodlife.com]] |page= |date=October 14, 2011 |accessdate=September 8, 2016 |url=http://hollywoodlife.com/2011/10/14/penn-badgley-blair-waldorf-dan-humphry-soulmate-gossip-girl/}}</ref> and further stated that he thought the Blair and Dan storyline was \"the most exciting for Dan as a person\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Robyn |last=Ross |title=Gossip Girl's Leighton Meester: I Want the Blair and Dan Relationship to Play Out |work=[[TV Guide]] |page= |date=November 20, 2011 |accessdate=September 8, 2016 |url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/gossip-girl-leighton-meester-1039943/ }}</ref> When ''[[Hollywoodlife.com]]'' asked [[Ed Westwick]], who played Chuck Bass, which character he thought loved Blair more, Chuck or Dan, Westwick pointed to Badgley, saying \"definitely him.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Karlis |last=Nicole |title='Gossip Girl' Stars Ed Westick & Penn Badgley Reveal Who Loves Blair More |work=[[Hollywoodlife.com]] |page= |date=February 13, 2012 |accessdate=September 8, 2016 |url=http://hollywoodlife.com/2012/02/13/chuck-blair-dan-love-gossip-girl-season-5/}}</ref>\n\nProducers initially noticed chemistry between Blair and Dan in the {{nowrap|Season 1}} episode \"Bad News Blair\". According to producer Joshua Safran, the creators planned to revisit their relationship once the timing was right. Safran also stated that the outcome wasn't necessarily decided ahead of time. \"One thing we are very conscious of\u2014and I know some fans get upset about this\u2014is we really try to treat the characters as living, breathing, well-rounded individuals. And we're often surprised by where their journeys take them; they open new doors for us all the time,\" he said.<ref name=JS/>\n\n====Controversy====\nFollowing the {{nowrap|twentieth episode}} of {{nowrap|Season 4,}} Safran spoke on behalf of the series regarding the scene in which Chuck became violent with Blair.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Arrow |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'' Boss: \"Chuck Has Never, and Will Never, Hurt Blair\" |work=[[E!]] Online |page= |date=May 3, 2011 |accessdate=May 10, 2011 |url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/watch_with_kristin/b239902_gossip_girl_boss_chuck_has_never_will.html}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|The way we viewed it, I think it's very clear that Blair is not afraid in those moments, for herself. They have a volatile relationship, they always have, but I do not believe\u2014or I should say we do not believe\u2014that it is abuse when it's the two of them. Chuck does not try to hurt Blair. He punches the glass because he has rage, but he has never, and will never, hurt Blair. He knows it and she knows it, and I feel it's very important to know that she is not scared\u2014if anything, she is scared for Chuck\u2014and what he might do to himself, but she is never afraid of what he might do to her. Leighton and I were very clear about that.}}\n\nIn response to these comments, Carina MacKenzie of [[Zap2it]] stated, \"We're left wondering if Safran missed the part where she went home bleeding because Chuck was using physical intimidation to release his own emotions.\"<ref name=MacKenzie>{{cite news |first=Carina |last=MacKenzie |title=''Gossip Girl'': Is Chuck Bass abusive? E.P. says no; we beg to differ |work=Zap2it |date=May 3, 2011 |accessdate=May 10, 2011 |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/05/gossip-girl-is-chuck-bass-abusive-ep-says-no-we-beg-to-differ.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110507231323/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/05/gossip-girl-is-chuck-bass-abusive-ep-says-no-we-beg-to-differ.html |archivedate=May 7, 2011 }}</ref> While reviewing the episode, Tierney Bricker of Zap2it felt that there were \"really no excuses for Chuck Bass anymore.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Tierney |last=Bricker |title=Blair catches Royal Wedding fever |work=Zap2it |date=May 3, 2011 |accessdate=May 8, 2011 |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/05/gossip-girl-the-princesses-and-the-frog-blair-catches-royal-wedding-fever.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110507014356/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/05/gossip-girl-the-princesses-and-the-frog-blair-catches-royal-wedding-fever.html |archivedate=May 7, 2011 }}</ref> MacKenzie concluded that Chuck's behavior throughout {{nowrap|Season 4}} fit the signs of an [[Relational aggression|abusive relationship]], citing examples from ''HelpGuide.org'', a non-profit health resource. She noted Chuck's public humiliation of Blair, his attempt to pawn her during a business deal, and his use of physical intimidation. MacKenzie also called the show's explanation \"disturbing, particularly given the young, female target demographic of ''Gossip Girl'' and The CW.\"<ref name=MacKenzie/>\n\nIn a review for the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', Judy Berman addressed Safran's description of Blair during the scene. \"Considering how terrified Blair looked at the end of their encounter, and how quickly she got out of there, the show is sending a mixed message at best.\" She went on to state, \"We have no right to expect ''Gossip Girl'' to be a paragon of morality, or even realism, but the idea that true love requires taking a shard of glass to the face is disturbing even in this alternate, soap-opera dimension.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Judy |last=Berman |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'' recap: They tried to make Chuck go to rehab |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |page= |date=May 10, 2011 |accessdate=May 10, 2011 |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2011/05/gossip-girl-recap-they-tried-to-make-chuck-go-to-rehab.html}}</ref>\n\n===Season 5===\nIn the fifth-season premiere, Blair continues to plan her wedding, but begins to encounter problems in her relationship with Louis. It is later revealed that she is pregnant.<ref name=child/> Blair tells Chuck that the child is Louis', and states that part of her wanted Chuck to be the father.<ref>{{cite news |first=Dawn |last=Fallik |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'', Season 5, Episode 3, 'The Jewel of Denial': TV Recap |work=The Wall Street Journal |page= |date=October 10, 2011 |accessdate=October 11, 2011 |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2011/10/10/gossip-girl-season-5-episode-3-the-jewel-of-denial-tv-recap/?mod=google_news_blog}}</ref> Dan becomes Blair's confidante and is shown to be in love with her, though she remains oblivious to his feelings and states that there is nothing more than friendship between them.\n\nThough she insists that she is in love with Louis, Blair begins to seek Chuck out as the season progresses. The two eventually declare their love for each other prior to a car accident in her limousine while being chased by paparazzi. Though both recover, Blair suffers a miscarriage from the crash. After the crash Blair decides that she must commit herself to Louis, converting to [[Catholic Church|Catholicism]] and cutting off any connection with Chuck. At the wedding, Gossip Girl releases a recording of Blair confessing her love for Chuck. Nevertheless, Louis and Blair get married, making Blair a Princess of Monaco, though Louis informs her that they will have a loveless marriage of convenience.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |title= Gossip Girl's 100th Episode Shocker |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=January 30, 2012 |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2012/01/30/gossip-girl-blair-dan-wedding-100-episode/}}</ref> She then receives support from Dan, leading them to share a kiss on Valentine's Day. Amidst these developments, Blair grows conflicted between her feelings for Dan and Chuck.<ref>{{cite news |first=Laura |last=Prudom |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'' Recap: Dan And Blair Confront Their Feelings In 'Cross Rhodes' |work=Huffington Post |page= |date=February 21, 2012 |accessdate=February 22, 2012 |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/laura-prudom/gossip-girl-recap-cross-rhodes_b_1289931.html}}</ref> After taking steps to end her marriage, she chooses to begin a romantic relationship with Dan.<ref>{{cite news |first=Catriona |last=Wightman |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'': 'The Princess Dowry' recap |work=DigitalSpy.com |page= |date=February 28, 2012 |accessdate=March 3, 2012 |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/s83/gossip-girl/recaps/a368223/gossip-girl-the-princess-dowry-recap.html}}</ref> By the end of the season, however, after a debate about which love is the best\u2014with Dan she feels safe, with Chuck she feels vulnerable\u2014Blair declares that she is still in love with Chuck, and chooses to pursue him.<ref>{{cite news|first=Tierney |last=Bricker |title=''Gossip Girl'' Finale Redux: Blair Chooses Her Man! So What Comes Next? |work=E! |date=May 14, 2012 |accessdate=May 15, 2012 |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/watch_with_kristin/gossip_girl_finale_redux_blair_chooses/316189 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120516112642/http://www.eonline.com/news/watch_with_kristin/gossip_girl_finale_redux_blair_chooses/316189 |archivedate=May 16, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Season 6===\nIn the final season, Blair resumes her romantic relationship with Chuck, while Chuck and his father Bart\u2014who is revealed to be alive in the previous season\u2014become bitter rivals. Blair pursues her career as head of Waldorf Designs, with several mishaps, before staging a successful line.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wetpaint.com/gossip-girl-recap-of-season-7-episode-6-chuck-tells-blair-its-over-739230/ |title=Gossip Girl Recap of Season 6, Episode 7: Chuck Tells Blair It's Over |website=[[Wetpaint]] |date=November 27, 2012 |first=Whitney |last=Ricketts |accessdate=November 30, 2015}}</ref> In the penultimate episode, Bart falls to his death while trying to attack Chuck atop a building. Afterward, Blair and Chuck depart together. In the series finale, Blair marries Chuck which results in her not having to testify against him in his father's murder case. Five years later, Blair is shown to be running her mother's successful fashion line and she works with Jenny in a line called \"J for Waldorf\", and she and Chuck are shown to have a son named Henry.<ref>{{cite news |first=Dawn |last=Fallik |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'', Season 6, Episode 9, 'The Revengers': TV Recap |work=E! |page= |date=December 10, 2012 |accessdate=December 13, 2012 |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2012/12/10/gossip-girl-season-6-episode-9-the-revengers-tv-recap/}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===In print===\nWhile covering the book series, Janet Malcolm of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' labeled the character \"an [[antihero]]ine of the first rank,\" and asserted that \"the series belongs to awful Blair, who inspires von Ziegesar's highest flights of comic fancy.\" She also compared Blair to vintage film and literary figures such as [[Becky Sharp (character)|Becky Sharp]] of ''[[Vanity Fair (novel)|Vanity Fair]]'', and Lizzie Eustace of ''[[The Eustace Diamonds]]''.<ref name=NYreview/> In addition, several critics have likened Blair to the character Lila Fowler of the earlier ''[[Sweet Valley High]]'' series.<ref name=fowler=one/><ref name=fowler-two/><ref>{{cite news |first=Michelle |last=Ruiz |coauthors= |title=The Long-Awaited ''Sweet Valley High'' Movie Is Happening at Last |work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] |page= |date=July 31, 2017 |accessdate=September 1, 2018 |url=https://www.vogue.com/article/sweet-valley-high-movie}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2007 book ''Children's Literature and Culture'', writer Harry Edwin Eiss chastised the depiction of Blair's bulimia. \"If handled properly, the inclusion of her illness could have provided a powerful lesson for young adult readers who worry about their weight and food consumption. Unfortunately, Cecily von Ziegesar, the author of the series, presents a seriously flawed treatment of the problem. In a failed attempt at humor, the writer regards Blair's sickness as just another source of gossip,\" he said.<ref>{{cite news |first=Harry |last=Eiss |coauthors= |title=''Children's Literature and Culture'' |work=Cambridge Scholars Publishing |page=133 |year=2007 |accessdate=July 12, 2011 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xqYpAQAAIAAJ&dq=Children%27s+literature+and+culture&q=blair+waldorf+bulimic}}</ref> Emily Nussbaum of ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine had similar comments, calling the bulimia \"more of an icky weakness than a full-fledged pathology.\" However, she went on to commend Blair as \"hilariously self-centered\".<ref name=nyarticle/>\n\nJulie Opipari of ''Manga Maniac Cafe'' gave the initial ''Gossip Girl'' manga a negative review, citing displeasure with the characters and plot. However, she acknowledged that this gave her a greater appreciation for Blair in the second volume, noting that Blair \"really had to learn how to rough it\" after losing her privileged lifestyle. She went on to state that \"Blair is one character that is fun to hate on. So imagine my surprise when I actually started to like her by the end of the book\".<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Review: Gossip Girl: For Your Eyes Only V 2 |work=Manga Maniac Cafe |page= |date=December 22, 2011 |accessdate=February 23, 2012 |url=http://www.mangamaniaccafe.com/?p=5824 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208115950/http://www.mangamaniaccafe.com/?p=5824 |archive-date=December 8, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===On screen===\n[[File:Leightonchanel.jpg|thumb|170px|right|alt=Leighton Meester in a black dress|Meester's portrayal of Blair has been met with critical acclaim. The actress prepared by reading ''Gossip Girl''.<ref name=ctv/>]]\nThe show's [[List of breakout characters|breakout character]],<ref>{{cite news |first=Ben |last=Widdicombe |coauthors= |title=A ''Gossip Girl'' dropout |work=Daily News (New York)|page= |date=April 9, 2008 |accessdate=October 3, 2009 |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/gossip/2008/04/09/2008-04-09_a_gossip_girl_dropout__or_did_leighton_m.html}}</ref> Blair Waldorf has garnered much media recognition. ''Yahoo!'' proclaims Blair a member of \"television's pantheon of razor-witted, solipsistic high school Alpha females.\"<ref name=YahooReview/> While commenting on Meester, ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine's 2008 cover story of the series states, \"Her villain-you-want-to-root-for is the most sophisticated performance on the show.\"<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=The Genius of ''Gossip Girl'' |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |page= |date= |accessdate=July 24, 2009 |url=http://nymag.com/arts/tv/features/46225/index4.html}}</ref> In another 2008 article, ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine commented that \"Meester has burst out of this ensemble to stardom.\"<ref name=pmag>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Leighton Meester |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |page= |date= |accessdate=October 9, 2008|url=http://www.people.com/people/leighton_meester}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' described her performance as similar to that of \"a predatory junior [[Joan Collins]] who practically breathes fire out of her pinched, perfectly WASP-ish nostrils.\"<ref name=pmag/> ''[[FHM]] Online'' ranked the actress the \"Hottest TV Star\" of autumn 2008, stating that as Blair Waldorf, \"Leighton Meester has stolen the spotlight with her mind-blowing good looks and amazing performance.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=''Gossip Girl'' Meester TV's Hottest star|work=[[Reuters]]|date=September 22, 2008|accessdate=October 30, 2011|url=http://blogs.reuters.com/fanfare/2008/09/22/gossip-girl-meester-tvs-hottest-star-kath-kim-a-bomb-fhm/|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080925053929/http://blogs.reuters.com/fanfare/2008/09/22/gossip-girl-meester-tvs-hottest-star-kath-kim-a-bomb-fhm/|archivedate=September 25, 2008}}</ref> ''[[OK!]]'' magazine likened her character to [[Audrey Hepburn]]'s portrayal of Holly Golightly.<ref name=OKmag>{{cite news|title=OK! Interview: Leighton Meester |work=[[OK!]] |date=September 18, 2008 |accessdate=October 4, 2009 |url=http://www.okmagazine.com/2008/09/ok-interview-leighton-meester-9072/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204132059/http://www.okmagazine.com/2008/09/ok-interview-leighton-meester-9072/ |archivedate=December 4, 2010 }}</ref> The physical similarity was also noted by ''[[USA Today]]''.<ref>{{cite news |first=Craig |last=Wilson |coauthors= |title=Here's A Toast To 'Tiffany's' On Landmark Novel's 50th Birthday |work=[[USA Today]] |page= |date=October 28, 2008 |accessdate=November 23, 2010 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/books/news/2008-10-28-tiffanys_N.htm}}</ref>\n\nIn its 2009 \"Hot List\", ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' cited Blair as \"the reason we love the back-stabby soap most.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Jason |last=Gay |title=Gossip Girl's Leighton Meester; our 2009 hot list leader |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=July 9, 2009 |url=http://music.ninemsn.com.au/blog.aspx?blogentryid=288940&showcomments=true |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929121654/http://music.ninemsn.com.au/blog.aspx?blogentryid=288940&showcomments=true |archivedate=September 29, 2011 }}</ref> Regarding the fictional fame of Blair's friend Serena, Tim Stack of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' asserted that \"Serena may be the star of the media but Blair is quickly becoming the star of this show.\"<ref>{{cite news |first= Tim|last= Stack|coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'': Yale and Hearty |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |page= |date= October 14, 2008|accessdate=February 22, 2009 |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20232869,00.html}}</ref> While citing Serena's long-revered allure, ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'' and its readers compared the two characters in 2008, with Blair being recognized as more beautiful than Serena.<ref>{{cite news |first= Petra|last= Guglielmetti|coauthors= |title=Who's Prettier: Blair or Serena? |work=[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]] |page= |date=October 14, 2008 |accessdate=July 5, 2009|url=http://www.glamour.com/beauty/blogs/girls-in-the-beauty-department/2008/10/whos-prettier-blair-or-serena.html}}</ref> In a review from ''[[The Atlantic]]'', Blair and Serena's friendship was praised as \"it offered a relationship whose depth and complexity approached [[Rory Gilmore and Paris Geller|Rory and Paris]]' [from ''[[Gilmore Girls]]''].\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Li|first1=Shirley|title=When Paris Met Rory: TV's Last Great Teenage-Girl Friendship|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2014/10/tvs-female-friendships-should-follow-rory-and-paris-lead-from-gilmore-girls/380957/|website=[[The Atlantic]]|accessdate=August 22, 2015|date=October 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, Blair received attention from ''[[Forbes]]'', which interviewed her via the series' writers.<ref>{{cite news |first= Anna|last= Broek|coauthors= |title=The Forbes Fictional Interview: Blair Waldorf |work=[[Forbes]] |page= |date=May 13, 2009 |accessdate=July 5, 2009|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/05/13/gossip-girl-interview-leadership-waldorf.html}}</ref> ''[[Television Without Pity]]'' listed Meester in their \"[[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globes]] 2009: Overlooked TV Shows and Performances\" article, labeling Blair \"so multi-faceted, well-dressed and beautifully played that she elevates this teen soap to something we don't even feel guilty about admitting we love.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Golden Globes 2009: Overlooked TV Shows and Performances |work=Television Without Pity |url=http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/show/golden_globes/golden_globes_2009_overlooked_1.php |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091223070026/http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/show/golden_globes/golden_globes_2009_overlooked_1.php |archivedate=2009-12-23 }}</ref> Meester won the [[Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Award]] for \"Choice TV Actress Drama\" in 2009,<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Teen Choice Award Winners |work=[[CBS]] |page= |date=August 10, 2009 |accessdate=August 26, 2009 |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/08/10/entertainment/main5229758.shtml}}</ref> and again in 2010.<ref>{{cite news |first=Natalie |last=Finn |coauthors= |title=Teens Deem Kardashians Choice Reality TV |work=[[E!]] |page= |date= August 8, 2010 |accessdate=August 9, 2010 |url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/b194308_teens_deem_kardashians_choice_reality_tv.html}}</ref> In 2009, she was voted the \"Best Mean Girl\" in Zap2it{{'s}} first poll of the best television characters in the 2000s.<ref>{{cite web|last=Grieser |first=Andy |title=The decade's best television characters, according to you |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2009/08/the-decades-best-television-characters-according-to-you.html |work=Zap2it |publisher=[[Tribune Media Services]] |accessdate=September 18, 2012 |date=August 25, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100918190838/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2009/08/the-decades-best-television-characters-according-to-you.html |archivedate=September 18, 2010 }}</ref> In February 2012, Zap2it held another poll to determine TV's Most Crushworthy. Blair was elected TV's Most Crushworthy 1% Female over [[Temperance \"Bones\" Brennan]].<ref>{{cite web|title=TV's Most Crushworthy 1% (Female) |url=http://www.zap2it.com/news/pictures/zap-tv-most-crushworthy-awards-pics,0,2089692.photogallery?index=21 |work=Zap2it |publisher=Tribune Media Services |accessdate=May 19, 2012 |author=MacKenzie, Carina Adly |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511051125/http://www.zap2it.com/news/pictures/zap-tv-most-crushworthy-awards-pics%2C0%2C2089692.photogallery?index=21 |archivedate=May 11, 2012 }}</ref> The 1 percenters are people that \"have everything going for them with their fantastic good looks and their opulent lifestyle\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Eckstein|first=David|title=TV's Most Crushworthy - The 1 percenters: 'Gossip Girl' stars Ed Westwick and Leighton Meester take on Emily Deschanel and Justin Hartley|url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2012/02/tvs-most-crushworthy---the-1-percenters-gossip-girl-stars-ed-westwick-and-leighton-meester-take-on-e.html|work=[[Zap2it]]|accessdate=May 19, 2012|date=February 23, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512052213/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2012/02/tvs-most-crushworthy---the-1-percenters-gossip-girl-stars-ed-westwick-and-leighton-meester-take-on-e.html|archivedate=May 12, 2012}}</ref> Her relationship with [[Chuck Bass]] was included in ''[[TV Guide]]''{{'s}} list of \"The Best TV Couples of All Time\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Couples Pictures, Gossip Girl Photos - Photo Gallery: The Best TV Couples of All Time |url=http://www.tvguide.com/PhotoGallery/Best-TV-Couples-1026715/1026739 |work=[[TV Guide]] |accessdate=June 20, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925233416/http://www.tvguide.com/PhotoGallery/Best-TV-Couples-1026715/1026739 |archivedate=September 25, 2012 }}</ref> as well as ''Entertainment Weekly''{{'s}} \"30 Best 'Will They/Won't They?' TV Couples\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bierly|first1=Mandi|last2=Fog|first2=Henning|title=30 Best 'Will They/Won't They?' TV Couples &#124; Photo 21 of 30|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20304425_21156349,00.html#20670143|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time Inc]]|accessdate=July 7, 2012|date=May 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe character's wardrobe\u2014credited to designers Abigail Lorick and Eric Daman<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Designers to Watch: Abigail Lorick |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |page= |date=August 29, 2008 |accessdate=October 30, 2011 |url=http://nymag.com/daily/fashion/2008/08/designer_abigail_lorick.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first= Margy|last= Rochlin|coauthors= |title=Eric Daman: ''Gossip Girl'' |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |page= |date=June 7, 2009|accessdate=July 5, 2009|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/07/arts/television/07dama.html}}</ref>\u2014was popular, earning mentions from periodicals such as ''[[InStyle]]''<ref name=instyle>{{cite news|title=''Gossip Girl'' Season One: Get the Look |work=[[InStyle]] |date=September 19, 2008 |accessdate=October 9, 2008 |url=http://www.instyle.com/instyle/package/general/photos/0,,20164507_20057738_20371760,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081019191151/http://www.instyle.com/instyle/package/general/photos/0%2C%2C20164507_20057738_20371760%2C00.html |archivedate=October 19, 2008 }}</ref> and ''New York'',<ref name=nymag>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Blair Waldorf's Wardrobe Does Not Go Home With Her |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |page= |date=March 19, 2008 |accessdate=October 9, 2008 |url=http://nymag.com/daily/fashion/2008/03/blair_waldorfs_wardrobe_does_n.html}}</ref> along with recognition from websites.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Blair Waldorf's Signature Looks |work=ctv.ca |page= |date= |accessdate=October 9, 2008 |url=http://www.ctv.ca/gallery/html/gg_blair_looks_071126/photo_0.html}}</ref> ''TV Guide'' listed Blair among its \"Best Dressed TV Characters of 2007\".<ref>{{cite news|title=The Best Dressed TV Characters of 2007 |work=[[TV Guide]] |date=Autumn 2007 |accessdate=October 30, 2011 |url=http://www.tvguide.com/PhotoGallery/Best-Dressed-TV-1680/2665 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120913013929/http://www.tvguide.com/PhotoGallery/Best-Dressed-TV-1680/2665 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-09-13 }}</ref> ''Entertainment Weekly'' named Blair Waldorf and Chuck Bass the \"Most Stylish\" characters of 2008.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=The Best & Worst of 2008 |work=Entertainment Weekly |page= |date= |accessdate=July 9, 2009|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20162677_20164091_20243883_9,00.html}}</ref> [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] television ranks Blair first in its listing of \"The Top 10 Best-Dressed TV Characters\",<ref>{{cite news|first=Melissa |last=Kagan |title=Top 10 Best-Dressed TV Characters |work=[[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] |accessdate=July 9, 2009 |url=http://www.mylifetime.com/lifestyle/beauty-style/celebrity-style/top-10-best-dressed-tv-characters#id=1 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090613070511/http://www.mylifetime.com/lifestyle/beauty-style/celebrity-style/top-10-best-dressed-tv-characters |archivedate=June 13, 2009 }}</ref> while ''Glamour'' has named her among its best-dressed TV characters of all time.<ref>{{cite news |first=Tracey |last=Lomrantz |coauthors= |title=Meet The 9 Best Dressed TV Characters Of All Time |work=Glamour |page= |date=September 26, 2008 |accessdate=July 9, 2009|url=http://www.glamour.com/fashion/blogs/slaves-to-fashion/2008/09/meet-the-9-best-dressed-tv-cha.html}}</ref> In a ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' interview, costume designers Eric Daman and Meredith Markworth-Pollack named Audrey Hepburn and ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' editor-in-chief [[Anna Wintour]] as their inspirations when dressing Meester as Blair. The designers also cited New York socialites [[Tinsley Mortimer]] and Arden Wohl as influences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/online/daily/2008/04/welcome-back-go.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110301202401/http://www.vanityfair.com/online/daily/2008/04/welcome-back-go.html |archivedate=March 1, 2011 |title=Welcome Back, Gossip Girl |work=Vanity Fair |date=March 17, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''TV Guide'' named her the sixth most fashionable TV character.<ref>{{cite web|title=Blair Waldorf Pictures - Photo Gallery: Who Are the Most Fashionable TV Characters? |url=http://www.tvguide.com/PhotoGallery/Fashionable-TV-Characters-1044392/1044402 |work=TV Guide |accessdate=September 14, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002014214/http://www.tvguide.com/PhotoGallery/Fashionable-TV-Characters-1044392/1044402 |archivedate=October 2, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n;Books\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last=von Ziegesar |first=Cecily |title=Gossip Girl: Because I'm Worth It |publisher=Poppy ([[Little, Brown and Company]]) |year=2003 |pages= |isbn=978-0-316-90968-6 |url=https://archive.org/details/becauseimworthit00vonz }}\n*{{cite book|last=von Ziegesar |first=Cecily |title=You Know You Love Me: A Gossip Girl Novel |url=https://archive.org/details/youknowyouloveme00litt |url-access=registration |publisher=Poppy (Little, Brown and Company) |year=2002 |pages= |isbn=978-0-316-91148-1}}\n*{{cite book |last=von Ziegesar |first=Cecily |title=Gossip Girl: I Will Always Love You |publisher=Poppy (Little, Brown and Company) |year=2009 |pages= |isbn=978-0-316-04361-8 |url=https://archive.org/details/gossipgirliwilla00ceci_0 }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{Gossip Girl}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Waldorf, Blair}}\n[[Category:Gossip Girl characters]]\n[[Category:Characters in American novels of the 21st century]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2002]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters from New York City]]\n[[Category:Fictional socialites]]\n[[Category:Fictional princesses]]\n[[Category:Fictional Monegasque people]]\n[[Category:Fictional bullies]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with body dysmorphia]]\n[[Category:Teenage characters in television]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with bulimia]]\n[[Category:Fictional Yale University people]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color     = #F0E68C\n| name      = Blair Waldorf\n| series    = [[Gossip Girl (novel series)|Gossip Girl]]\n| image     = GGBlaircover.jpg\n| alt       = A brunette, female model in a dress\n| caption   = Blair as portrayed on the cover of ''It Had To Be You''\n| first     = '''Novel''': <br>''[[Gossip Girl (novel series)#Gossip Girl|Gossip Girl]]'' <br>'''Television''': <br>\"[[Pilot (Gossip Girl)|Pilot]]\" <br>(episode 1.01)\n| last      = '''Novel''': <br> ''[[Gossip Girl (novel series)#Gossip Girl|I Will Always Love You]]''  <br>'''Television''': <br>\"[[New York, I Love You XOXO]]\" <br>(episode 6.10)\n| creator   = '''Character''' <br>[[Cecily von Ziegesar]] <br>'''Television producers''' <br>[[Josh Schwartz]] <br>[[Stephanie Savage]]\n| portrayer = [[Leighton Meester]]\n| full_name = Blair Cornelia Waldorf\n| alias     = B, Queen B\n| spouse    = '''Television''': <br>[[Chuck Bass|Charles \"Chuck\" Bass]] <br>(husband) <br>[[List of Gossip Girl characters#Louis Grimaldi|Prince Louis Grimaldi]] <br>(ex-husband)\n| title     = '''Television:''' <br>Princess Blair of Monaco <br>(during her marriage to [[List of Gossip Girl characters#Louis Grimaldi|Louis]])\n| family    = [[List of Gossip Girl characters#Harold Waldorf|Harold]] and [[List of Gossip Girl characters#Eleanor Waldorf|Eleanor Waldorf]]<br>(parents) <br>[[List of Gossip Girl characters#Cyrus Rose|Cyrus Rose]] <br>(stepfather) <br>[[List of Gossip Girl characters#Guest stars|Aaron Rose]]<br>(stepbrother) <br>'''Novels:''' <br>Tyler Waldorf<br>(younger brother) <br>Ying and Yang Waldorf<br>(adoptive sister and brother)<br>Yale Waldorf-Rose <br>(half-sister)\n| children  = '''Television''':<br>Henry Bass <br>(son, with Chuck; [[New York, I Love You XOXO|flash-forward]])\n}}\n'''Blair Cornelia Waldorf'''<!-- Please do not add a name from the TV series --><ref>von Ziegesar, ''Gossip Girl: I Will Always Love You'', p. 336</ref> is one of the main characters of ''[[Gossip Girl (novel series)|Gossip Girl]]'',<ref>{{cite news |first=James |last=Morrison |coauthors= |title=Protests at sex and drugs in teen publishing sensation |work=arlindo-correia.org |page= |date=August 25, 2002 |accessdate=December 2, 2010 |url=http://www.arlindo-correia.org/120103.html}}</ref> introduced in the original series of novels and also appearing in the [[Gossip Girl|television]] and [[comic]] adaptations. Described as \"a girl of extremes\" by creator [[Cecily von Ziegesar]],<ref>{{cite news|title=A Sheepish Interview with Cecily von Ziegesar |work=sheepishfashionista.com |date=October 5, 2010 |accessdate=December 2, 2010 |url=http://sheepishfashionista.com/2010/10/05/sheepish-interview-with-cecily-von-ziegesar-inspired-creator-original-gossip-girl/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110120224442/http://sheepishfashionista.com/2010/10/05/sheepish-interview-with-cecily-von-ziegesar-inspired-creator-original-gossip-girl/ |archivedate=January 20, 2011 }}</ref> she is a [[New York City]] socialite and a comical overachiever who possesses both snobbish and sensitive sides. Due to her position as [[Queen bee (subculture)|queen bee]] of [[Manhattan]]'s social scene, Blair's actions and relations are under constant scrutiny from the mysterious Gossip Girl, a popular [[blog]]ger.\n\n[[Leighton Meester]], who portrayed the character in the television drama, has described Blair as being insecure about her social status.<ref>{{cite news|title=''Gossip Girl'' Actress Spills the Beans on Her Character|work=buddytv.com|date=September 25, 2007|accessdate=October 9, 2008|url=http://www.buddytv.com/articles/gossip-girl/gossip-girl-the-new-cw-11418.aspx|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414201116/http://www.buddytv.com/articles/gossip-girl/gossip-girl-the-new-cw-11418.aspx|archive-date=2015-04-14|url-status=dead}}</ref> At times, this anxiety creates flaws and complexities which contribute to character development. In Meester's view, the true Blair is ultimately a good girl at heart.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Duck |first=Siobhan |url=http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/story/0,23739,22943161-5003422,00.html |title=Queen bee is really a good girl |publisher= The Courier-Mail |date=2007-12-20 |work=news.com.au |access-date=2020-04-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071220221828/http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/story/0,23739,22943161-5003422,00.html |archive-date=December 20, 2007}}</ref>\n\nBlair has been compared to vintage film and literary figures, including [[Becky Sharp (character)|Becky Sharp]] and [[The Eustace Diamonds|Lizzie Eustace]]. She is commonly likened to Lila Fowler of Francine Pascal's ''[[Sweet Valley High]]'' series.<ref name=fowler=one>{{cite news |first=Amelia |last=McDonell-Parry |coauthors= |title=Casting the ''Sweet Valley High'' Movie |work=[[ABC News]] |page= |date=November 25, 2011 |accessdate=September 1, 2018 |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/sweet-valley-high-movie/story?id=15016223}}</ref><ref name=fowler-two>{{cite news |first=Zara |last=Husaini |coauthors= |title=Creating the ''Sweet Valley High'' Cast of My Dreams |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |page= |date=January 25, 2014 |accessdate=September 1, 2018 |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/zara-husaini/casting-and-styling-the-s_b_4298331.html}}</ref> Meester's portrayal has also drawn comparisons to roles played by [[Joan Collins]] and [[Audrey Hepburn]]. She is the most critically acclaimed character of the franchise, while the television character has drawn real-life attention surrounding fashion and her love life.\n\n==Character in print==\n''[[Gossip Girl (novel series)|Gossip Girl]]'' is a series of novels about socially prominent young adults in [[New York City]]. The story primarily follows Blair Waldorf and her best friend [[Serena van der Woodsen]] during their years in high school and college. Due to her fame on the [[Upper East Side]], Blair is featured on the website of \"Gossip Girl,\" an anonymous gossip [[blog]]ger whose posts appear occasionally throughout the story.\n\n===Novel series===\nIn the first book, Blair is introduced as a privileged, comically vain overachiever.<ref name=NYreview>{{cite news |first=Janet |last=Malcolm |coauthors= |title=The Wicked Joy of the ''Gossip Girl'' Novels |work=[[The New Yorker]] |page= |date=March 10, 2008 |accessdate=July 9, 2009 |url=http://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/atlarge/2008/03/10/080310crat_atlarge_malcolm}}</ref> She is described as an alluring brunette,<ref name=Blair>{{cite news |first=Cecily |last=von Ziegesar |coauthors= |title=''It Had To Be You: The Gossip Girl Prequel'' |work=Poppy (Little, Brown and Company) |page= |year=2009 |accessdate=July 12, 2011 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NF6T9CbK7h0C&printsec=frontcover&dq=It+Had+To+Be+You+Gossip+Girl#v=snippet&q=two%20hottest&f=false}}</ref> and occasionally models her appearance and demeanor after famous actresses, including [[Marilyn Monroe]] and, most often, [[Audrey Hepburn]].<ref>von Ziegesar, ''Gossip Girl: Because I'm Worth It'', p. 36</ref> In early novels, the character is also written as [[Bulimia nervosa|bulimic]].\n\nBlair is largely motivated by matters surrounding family, romance, and ambition. However, her tendency to overachieve can lead to feelings of paranoia, with dramatic or comical results. In a review for ''[[The New Yorker]]'', Janet Malcolm remarked that Blair's issues made her \"both a broader caricature and a more real person\" than the other ''Gossip Girl'' characters.<ref name=NYreview/> In a 2009 interview, ''Gossip Girl'' creator [[Cecily von Ziegesar]] claimed to identify with Blair the most, stating, \"She is so unpredictable and dramatic. Such a bitch, but we understand why she is a bitch and we like her anyway\".<ref name=qa>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Hon \u00e4r en s\u00e5n bitch |work=aftonbladet.se |page= |date=March 26, 2009 |accessdate=July 16, 2011 |url=http://www.aftonbladet.se/nojesbladet/article4748648.ab?service=print}}</ref>\n\n====Story lines====\nThroughout most of the series' run, Blair grapples with a number of changes within her family. One year prior to the opening novel, Blair's parents divorced after her father ran off with another man. When her mother remarries, and her father leaves the country, Blair has difficulty accepting her stepfather, Cyrus Rose. In addition, her stress over these matters occasionally affects her other relationships.<ref>von Ziegesar, ''You Know You Love Me: A Gossip Girl Novel'', p. 30</ref> However, Blair ultimately remains close to her father Harold, who she often turns to for comfort.<ref>von Ziegesar, ''You Know You Love Me: A Gossip Girl Novel'', p. 3</ref> By contrast, she maintains a somewhat tenser relationship with her mother Eleanor. It is also revealed that Blair has struggled with [[bulimia]].<ref>von Ziegesar, ''Gossip Girl: Because I'm Worth It'', p. 81</ref>\n\nIn the opening novel, Blair learns of an affair between her friend Serena and her boyfriend Nate. This marks the beginning of the story's primary [[love triangle]], which recurs throughout the series.<ref>{{cite news |first=Shannon |last=Maughan |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Got Legs |work=[[Publishers Weekly]] |page= |date=May 11, 2007 |accessdate=November 30, 2015 |url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/new-titles/adult-announcements/article/1412-gossip-girl-s-got-legs.html}}</ref> Blair's romantic life has various effects on her character development. After Nate repeatedly hurts her, she eventually refuses to take him back until she believes in his ability to commit to her.<ref>{{cite news |first=Cecily |last=von Ziegesar |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl: I Will Always Love You'' \"The Honest Truth and Other Rewards\" |work=Poppy (Little, Brown and Company) |page= |year=2009 |accessdate=July 23, 2011 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=md8WgIIJjSUC&q=four+months+ago#v=snippet&q=four%20months%20ago&f=false}}</ref> In pursuing Nate, however, Blair herself cheats on her new boyfriend Pete, which results in her losing both of them.<ref>{{cite news |first=Cecily |last=von Ziegesar |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl: I Will Always Love You'' |work=Poppy (Little, Brown and Company) |page= |year=2009 |accessdate=July 23, 2011 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=md8WgIIJjSUC&q=love+triangle+Pete#v=snippet&q=love%20triangle%20Pete&f=false}}</ref> She eventually begins to acknowledge her mistakes, with her father's help.<ref name=IWA>{{cite news |first=Cecily |last=von Ziegesar |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl: I Will Always Love You'' |work=Poppy (Little, Brown and Company) |page= |year=2009 |accessdate=July 12, 2011 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=md8WgIIJjSUC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Gossip+Girl:+I+Will+Always+Love+You#v=onepage&q=Harold&f=false}}</ref> She later grows closer to [[Chuck Bass]] (which initially occurred in the series' television adaptation), who she'd previously known for years, which leads them to briefly date one another.<ref name=IWA/>\n\nBlair is noted for an over-achieving nature, which often appears in humorous scenes. In a review for ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine, [[Emily Nussbaum]] lauded one of Blair's fantasies, which involves \"joining the Peace Corps, getting a killer tan, winning the Nobel Peace Prize, and having dinner with the president, 'who would then write her a recommendation to [[Yale University|Yale]], and then Yale would fall all over themselves to accept her.' \"<ref name=nyarticle>{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Nussbaum |authorlink=Emily Nussbaum |title=Psst, Serena is a slut. Pass it on |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |page= |date=May 21, 2005 |accessdate=July 12, 2011 |url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/arts/books/12058/}}</ref> ''The New Yorker''{{'s}} Janet Malcolm remarked that unlike some of her forerunners in film and literature, \"Blair already has all the money and position anyone could want. She is pure naked striving, restlessly seeking an object, any object, and never knowing when enough is enough.\"<ref name=NYreview/>\n\nBlair encounters a setback during her interview at Yale by revealing the recent stress in her life, and then kissing her interviewer on the cheek upon dismissal. Her father then makes a donation to the school, though Blair is still wait-listed.<ref>{{cite news |first=Cecily |last=von Ziegesar |coauthors= |title=''All I Want Is Everything: A Gossip Girl Novel'' |work=Poppy (Little, Brown and Company) |page= |year=2003 |accessdate=July 12, 2011 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qEE8K98qfkQC&pg=PA5&dq=Gossip+Girl+Yale+donate#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> In the twelfth book, ''I Will Always Love You'', it is revealed that she has been admitted to the university.<ref>von Ziegesar, ''Gossip Girl: I Will Always Love You'', p. 9</ref>\n\nIn addition to her feelings for Nate, Blair is sometimes said to feel competitive with Serena in other areas, including matters of beauty and popularity.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Cecily von Ziegesar Biography |work=bookrags.com |page= |date= |accessdate=July 16, 2011 |url=http://www.bookrags.com/biography/cecily-von-ziegesar-aya/}}</ref> This also leads to an occasional envy on Blair's part.<ref name=nyarticle/> It is unclear how much of Blair's perception of Serena is in line with reality; the narrative describes both characters as \"hands down the two hottest girls on the Upper East Side, and maybe all of Manhattan, or even the whole world.\"<ref name=Blair/>\n\n===Manga series===\n[[File:MangaBWaldorf.jpg|thumb|130px|right|alt=A manga drawing of Blair Waldorf|Blair as she appears in the manga.]]\nIn 2010, [[Yen Press]] began publishing a [[manga]] adaptation titled ''Gossip Girl: For Your Eyes Only'', written and illustrated by HyeKyung Baek. This series adapts notable scenarios from the novel\u2014including the triangle with Nate and Serena\u2014but also features new material.\n\nAfter losing her position as queen bee, Blair attempts to regain her former status while adjusting to a less privileged lifestyle.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gossip Girl: The Manga, Vol. 2|work=hachettebookgroup.com|accessdate=July 30, 2011|url=http://www.hachettebookgroup.com/books_9780759530270.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110323221422/http://www.hachettebookgroup.com/books_9780759530270.htm|archive-date=2011-03-23|url-status=dead}}</ref> In addition to this series, Blair also appears in a manga adaptation of the novel ''Gossip Girl: Psycho Killer'', a parody of horror stories.<ref>{{cite news |first=Kat |last=Rosenfield |title=''Gossip Girl: Psycho Killer'' Special Edition Manga: EXCLUSIVE First Look! |work=mtv.com |date=July 25, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2011 |url=http://hollywoodcrush.mtv.com/2011/07/25/gossip-girl-psycho-killer-exclusive/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208070552/http://hollywoodcrush.mtv.com/2011/07/25/gossip-girl-psycho-killer-exclusive/ |archivedate=February 8, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Television series==\nIn 2007, ''Gossip Girl'' was [[Gossip Girl|adapted for television]]. According to Cecily von Ziegesar, the television character is largely faithful to the original.<ref name=qa/> Among the aspects to be maintained are her admiration for Audrey Hepburn and her interest in Yale University. However, the series is also noted for its deviations from the source material,<ref name=NYreview/> including the exclusion of Blair's brother Tyler. The show also explores romances between Blair and multiple male leads, resulting in occasional love triangles. In the fifth season, Blair is revealed to be pregnant with Prince of Monaco, Louis Grimaldi's child. However the child later dies before birth after a car crash Blair and Chuck were in.<ref name=child>{{cite news |first= Dawn|last= Fallik|coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'' Season 5, Episode 1, 'Yes, Then Zero': TV Recap |work=The Wall Street Journal |page= |date=September 26, 2011 |accessdate=September 27, 2011 |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2011/09/26/gossip-girl-season-5-episode-1-yes-then-zero-tv-recap/}}</ref>\n\nAmong fans and the media, Blair's bond with Chuck Bass was commonly known by the portmanteau \"Chair\", while her relationship with Dan Humphrey was referred to as \"Dair\". The nicknames and viewer interest in these relationships were recognized by the show's producers.<ref>{{cite news |first=Vlada |last=Gelman |coauthors= |title=Gossip Girl Boss Previews Blair and Her Men, Serena's New Life, and Exploiting the UES\n |work=tvline.com |page= |date=September 1, 2011 |accessdate=September 13, 2011 |url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/09/gossip-girl-season-5-preview-josh-safran/}}</ref>\n \n===Casting===\n\n{{quote|They were like, 'Be bitchy and nice, ugly and pretty, young and old, stupid and smart, innocent and slutty, blond and brunette. Can you be all those things?'|4=Leighton Meester <ref>{{cite news|first=Jason |last=Gay |title=Dirty Pretty Things |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=November 23, 2010 |url=http://chaceconline.com/press/news.php?newsid=63 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120707050057/http://chaceconline.com/press/news.php?newsid=63 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 7, 2012 }}</ref>}}\n\nTo prepare for the part of Blair, actress [[Leighton Meester]], a natural blonde, dyed her hair brown before auditioning, and also studied the first novel.<ref name=peoplebio>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Leighton Meester biography |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |page= |date=November 25, 2008 |accessdate=September 27, 2009 |url=http://www.people.com/people/leighton_meester/biography}}</ref><ref name=ctv>{{cite news |first=Tyrone |last=Warner |coauthors= |title=Leighton Meester won't let ''Gossip Girl'' fans down |work=ctv.ca |page= |date= |accessdate=October 9, 2008 |url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/show/CTVShows/20071031/gg_meester_interview_071031/20071101/}}</ref> She has described the character as multi-faceted, labeling her \"a little bit of everything which is pretty amazing.\"<ref name=ctv/> Like von Ziegesar, Meester has also claimed to relate to Blair on certain levels. Prior to the show's debut in 2007, the actress stated that, \"The only way to play Blair, or any character, and make her human, is to find what she is inside me. And I know I have my insecurities, too.\" She went on to say that, \"The way Blair and I are ''not'' alike when it comes to insecurities is: ''She'' pays ''so'' much attention to hers!\"<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Leighton Meester: rich on 'Gossip Girl' |work=[[Associated Press]] |page= |date=September 12, 2007 |accessdate=August 11, 2010 |url=http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/Entertainment/20070912/leighton_gossip_070912/}}</ref> Meester's casting was described by ''[[Yahoo!]]'' as a star-making role which moved her \"into the pop culture vanguard,\"<ref name=YahooReview>{{cite news |title=Leighton Meester |work=[[Yahoo!]] |page= |date= |accessdate=July 9, 2009|url=https://tv.yahoo.com/leighton-meester/contributor/713039}}</ref> while Cecily von Ziegesar has called her a perfect choice.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jocelyn |last=Vena |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'' Author Is A 'Faithful Watcher' Of The TV Series |work=[[MTV]] |page= |date=October 16, 2008 |accessdate=October 4, 2009 |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1597121/20081015/index.jhtml}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, Meester revealed plans to leave the show in 2012. ''[[E!]] Online'' and other outlets speculated that her departure would possibly mark the end of the series.<ref name=Announcement>{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Malkin |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'': Getting Ready to End? |work=[[E!]] |page= |date=December 13, 2010 |accessdate=December 12, 2012 |url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/marc_malkin/b215864_gossip_girl_getting_ready_end.html}}</ref>\n\n===Season 1===\n{{Main|List of Gossip Girl episodes}}\n[[File:BWaldorf lead.jpg|thumb|170px|right|alt=Screenshot of Leighton Meester in 'Gossip Girl'|Blair as she appears in the TV adaptation, portrayed by Leighton Meester.]]\nIn {{nowrap|Season 1}} of ''Gossip Girl'', Blair is introduced as the Upper East Side's beautiful and popular [[Queen bee (sociology)|queen bee]]. She is the daughter of Eleanor Waldorf, a famous fashion designer. She is dating Nate Archibald, and is best friends with Serena van der Woodsen. She also finds a close companion in Nate's best friend and her childhood friend Chuck Bass, who becomes a partner for her schemes. When Serena returns home from boarding school, Blair learns from Nate that he lost his virginity to a drunken Serena over a year ago.<ref>{{cite news|title=''Gossip Girl'': \"The Wild Bunch\" |work=cwtv.com |accessdate=July 16, 2011 |url=http://www.cwtv.com/shows/gossip-girl/episodes/101 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110824071609/http://www.cwtv.com/shows/gossip-girl/episodes/101 |archivedate=August 24, 2011 }}</ref> Blair retaliates by publicly revealing Serena's connection to a rehab hospital. She then learns that the actual patient is Serena's younger brother, Eric, who had been committed after a suicide attempt. Afterward, a remorseful Blair reconciles with Serena.<ref>{{cite news|title=''Gossip Girl'': \"Poison Ivy\" |work=cwtv.com |accessdate=July 16, 2011 |url=http://www.cwtv.com/shows/gossip-girl/episodes/102 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110828065358/http://www.cwtv.com/shows/gossip-girl/episodes/102 |archivedate=August 28, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'' Rundown: Episode 3, \"Poison Ivy\" |work=buzzsugar.com |page= |date=October 7, 2011 |accessdate=July 16, 2011 |url=http://www.buzzsugar.com/Gossip-Girl-Rundown-Episode-3-Poison-Ivy-676065}}</ref>\n\nAfter learning that Nate no longer loves her, Blair sleeps with Chuck, eventually falling for him. This leads to a heated affair and an eventual love triangle. Her inability to choose creates much of the first season's story line.<ref>{{cite news|title=''Gossip Girl'': \"Hi, Society\" |work=cwtv.com |accessdate=July 16, 2011 |url=http://www.cwtv.com/shows/gossip-girl/episodes/109 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120122213350/http://www.cwtv.com/shows/gossip-girl/episodes/109 |archivedate=January 22, 2012 }}</ref> There are brief mentions of Blair's past struggle with anorexia-bulimia that are never mentioned again past the first season.\n\nShe also begins a brief power struggle with freshman [[Jenny Humphrey]]. After she unites with Chuck and Nate in order to save Serena from the scheming [[Georgina Sparks]], Chuck realizes that his feelings for Blair are real and suggests that they spend the summer together in Tuscany. However, he is discouraged by his father at the last minute, and stands Blair up.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Gossip Girl Recap: Episode 18, \"Much 'I Do' About Nothing\" |work=buzzsugar.com |page= |date=May 20, 2008 |accessdate=July 16, 2011 |url=http://www.buzzsugar.com/Gossip-Girl-Recap-Episode-18-Much-I-Do-About-Nothing-1645841}}</ref>\n\n===Season 2===\nAt the launch of the second season, Blair was described by creators as the [[Queen (chess)|queen]] at the center of the ''Gossip Girl'' chess game.<ref name=pmagazine>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Scene Stealers: The TV Stars We Had to Watch |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |page= |date=November 25, 2008 |accessdate=September 25, 2009 |url=http://www.people.com/people/package/gallery/0,,20240653_20241971,00.html}}</ref> A large portion of her story line in {{nowrap|Season 2}} revolves around her love-hate relationship with Chuck Bass, which was labeled \"the heart of ''GG''\" by ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine.<ref name=peoplebio/> While competing with Serena, Blair forms an unexpected friendship with Jenny, who states that they each work for everything they achieve, while Serena often glides through life. During their interviews at Yale University, Blair and Serena apologize for their ill feelings and resume their friendship.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'': \"New Haven Can Wait\" |work=Zap2it |page= |date= |accessdate=July 9, 2009|url=http://tvlistings.zap2it.com/tv/gossip-girl-new-haven-can-wait/EP009322060026}}</ref>\n\nIn the episode \"O Brother, Where Bart Thou?\", Chuck is devastated by news of his father's death, prompting Blair to offer her support while telling Chuck that she loves him. He initially shuns her advances, but later turns to her for comfort.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'': \"O Brother, Where Bart Thou?\" |work=Zap2it |page= |date= |accessdate=July 9, 2009|url=http://tvlistings.zap2it.com/tv/gossip-girl-o-brother-where-bart-thou/EP009322060033}}</ref> However, the two stop seeing each other due to Chuck's uncle, Jack Bass, convincing him he has an inability to commit to a relationship.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'': \"Gone with the Will\" |work=Zap2it |page= |date= |accessdate=July 9, 2009|url=http://tvlistings.zap2it.com/tv/gossip-girl-gone-with-the-will/EP009322060035}}</ref> After being rejected by Yale, Blair finds unexpected encouragement from Nate.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'': \"The Grandfather\" |work=Zap2it |page= |date= |accessdate=July 9, 2009|url=http://tvlistings.zap2it.com/tv/gossip-girl-the-grandfather/EP009322060042}}</ref> She is later accepted into New York University, and her competitive relationship with Georgina is eventually renewed.\n\nAs the season ends, Blair crowns Jenny the new queen of Constance Billard School. In the season finale, it is discovered that Blair slept with Chuck's uncle Jack and that Chuck had slept with Vanessa Abrams. Chuck then departs for Europe. He later returns to New York and reconciles with Blair while declaring his love for her, and the two finally begin a committed relationship.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'': \"The Goodbye Gossip Girl\" |work=[[TV Guide]] |page= |date= |accessdate=July 9, 2009|url=http://www.tvguide.com/detail/tv-show.aspx?tvobjectid=288136&more=ucepisodelist&episodeid=11183383}}</ref>\n\n===Season 3===\nIn the third season, Blair joins Vanessa, Georgina, and Jenny's brother Dan at NYU.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'': \"Reversals of Fortune\" |work=Zap2it |page= |date= |accessdate=October 3, 2009|url=http://tvlistings.zap2it.com/tv/gossip-girl-reversals-of-fortune/EP009322060046}}</ref> Much of her story line concerns her inability to attain her previous status at her new school. She finds emotional support from her mother, as well as Chuck. However, she and Chuck separate once again when Blair feels that he manipulated her while competing with his uncle (Chuck made a deal with Jack that Blair could sleep with him and in exchange, Chuck gets his hotel back that Jack initially stole to 'destroy Chuck').\n\nShe later transfers to Columbia University, and learns that an emotionally reformed Chuck was responsible for her enrollment.<ref>{{cite news |first=Gonzalez |last=Sandra |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'' recap: Chuck and Blair save each other |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |page= |date=May 4, 2010 |accessdate=August 25, 2009 |url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2010/05/04/gossip-girl-recap-ep-20-dad-world/?xid=rss-feed-tvwatch-%27Gossip+Girl%27+recap%3A+Chuck+and+Blair+save+each+other}}</ref> They later team up as part of a role-playing scheme to help Serena's mother and Chuck's adopted mother, Lily. In the season finale, Chuck attempts to propose to Blair, but is interrupted by Dan, who reveals that Chuck had slept with Jenny. Two weeks later, Blair and Serena depart for Paris intending to spend the summer together.<ref>{{cite news\n |first=Mark\n |last=Estes\n |title=Gossip Girl 3.22 \"Last Tango, Then Paris\" Recap/Review\n |work=tvovermind.Zap2it.com\n |date=May 18, 2010\n |accessdate=July 16, 2011\n |url=http://tvovermind.zap2it.com/thecw/gossip-girl/gossip-girl-3-22-review/23886\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718151414/http://tvovermind.zap2it.com/thecw/gossip-girl/gossip-girl-3-22-review/23886\n |archivedate=July 18, 2011\n}}</ref>\n\n===Season 4===\nIn {{nowrap|Season 4,}} Blair and Chuck become competitive once again, but eventually resume their sexual relations before recognizing their love for one another. When the relationship interferes with their business interests, she and Chuck break up once more. Chuck promises he'll wait for her, and both affirm their belief that their love will reunite them in the end.<ref>{{cite news |first=Hillary |last=Busis |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'' Season 4, Episode 9 'The Witches of Bushwick' |work=The Wall Street Journal |page= |date=November 16, 2010 |accessdate=July 16, 2011 |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2010/11/16/gossip-girl-season-4-episode-9-the-witches-of-bushwick/}}</ref>\n\nBlair then teams up with Dan when the two share common goals. They also end up working together at ''W.'' magazine, where friction develops between the two.<ref name=DB>{{cite news |first=Tierney |last=Bricker |title=''Gossip Girl''{{'s}} Leighton Meester talks Dan and Blair: 'I think they're good for each other' |work=[[Zap2it]] |date=February 1, 2011 |accessdate=March 28, 2011 |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/02/gossip-girls-leighton-meester-talks-dan-and-blair-i-think-theyre-good-for-each-other.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110408165853/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/02/gossip-girls-leighton-meester-talks-dan-and-blair-i-think-theyre-good-for-each-other.html |archivedate=April 8, 2011 }}</ref> On Valentine's Day, she discovers that Chuck has romantic feelings for Raina Thorpe, the daughter of his business rival. Later, she and Dan spend the evening talking on their cell phones while watching ''[[Rosemary's Baby (film)|Rosemary's Baby]]''.<ref>{{cite news |first=Tierney |last=Bricker |title=''Gossip Girl''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s 'It-Girl Happened One Night': A Valentine's Day 'Dair' |work=Zap2it |date=February 15, 2011 |accessdate=July 16, 2011 |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/02/gossip-girls-it-girl-happened-one-night-a-valentines-day-dair.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110324032322/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/02/gossip-girls-it-girl-happened-one-night-a-valentines-day-dair.html |archivedate=March 24, 2011 }}</ref> Blair later quits ''W.'' and is shown asleep with Dan in his Brooklyn flat. Later, upon growing curious of their feelings for one another, Blair and Dan share a kiss before the mid-season hiatus.\n\nBlair eventually decides that she wants to be with Chuck, but shuns him once again after he tries to humiliate Dan.<ref>{{cite news |first=Tierney |last=Bricker |title=The aftermath of Dan and Blair's kiss |work=Zap2it |date=April 18, 2011 |accessdate=May 8, 2011 |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/04/gossip-girl-the-kids-stay-in-the-picture-the-aftermath-of-dan-and-blairs-kiss.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110423083429/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/04/gossip-girl-the-kids-stay-in-the-picture-the-aftermath-of-dan-and-blairs-kiss.html |archivedate=April 23, 2011 }}</ref> She is later courted by a prince from Monaco named Louis. During a private confrontation, a drunken Chuck punches a window after he finds out Prince Louis has proposed to Blair, which cuts Blair's face as it shatters. Afterward, Blair chooses to accept a proposal from Louis.<ref>{{cite news |first=Ashley |last=Ostlie |coauthors= |title=Gossip Girl Episode Recap: \"The Princesses and the Frog\" |work=TV Guide |page= |date=May 3, 2011 |accessdate=May 8, 2011 |url=http://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/gossip-girl-2011/episode-20-season-4/princesses-frog/288136}}</ref> Blair later attempts to warn Chuck about potential trouble in his family. She is then abducted by an enemy of the Basses, Raina's father Russell Thorpe. Chuck later rescues Blair and apologizes for his violent actions. Following a night out together, the two have sex before Chuck advises Blair to return to Louis, believing that she will be happier with him. However, the season ends with the revelation that Blair may be pregnant.<ref>{{cite news |first= Dawn|last= Fallik|coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'', 'The Wrong Goodbye,' Recap |work=The Wall Street Journal |page= |date=May 16, 2011 |accessdate=May 17, 2011 |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2011/05/16/gossip-girl-the-wrong-goodbye-season-4-episode-22-tv-recap/}}</ref>\n\n====Reaction to triangle====\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float: right; margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 2em; font-size: 85%; background:#c6dbf7; color:black; width:25em; max-width: 40%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |Chuck and Blair are always going to be connected in their way, and Dan and Serena are always going to be connected in their way. But that doesn't mean that there won't be new roads to go down that might be different than what we initially anticipated.\n\u2014Joshua Safran, producer<ref name=JS>{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |title=''Gossip Girl'' Boss on the Big Dan/Blair Smooch: 'It Was a Long Time Coming' |work=TV Line |page= |date=March 1, 2011 |accessdate=March 28, 2011 |url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/03/gossip-girl-dan-blair-spoilers-kiss/}}</ref>\n|}\n\nAmidst the fourth season, the romance between Dan and Blair became a polarizing topic among viewers<ref name=DB/> which also drew significant media interest. Jarett Wieselman of the ''[[New York Post]]'' applauded the development, feeling that Blair had \"more chemistry\" with Dan than with Chuck.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jarett |last=Wieselman |title=IM-ing about ''Gossip Girl'' |work=[[New York Post]] |date=March 1, 2011 |accessdate=March 28, 2011 |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/im_ing_about_gossip_girl_rgTaVdXB87fbszlthtUVnM |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110306192342/http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/im_ing_about_gossip_girl_rgTaVdXB87fbszlthtUVnM |archivedate=March 6, 2011 }}</ref> ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine's Chris Rovzar called Blair and Dan's story line \"believable\", citing their common ground in education and taste. Rovzar further stated, \"Since they live in a world where both only seem to have half a dozen real friends (if that), is it so crazy they'd end up together?\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Rovzar |title=How the Writers of ''Gossip Girl'' Sold Us on the Show's Most Unbelievable Couple |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |page= |date=March 8, 2011 |accessdate=March 28, 2011 |url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2011/03/how_the_writers_of_gossip_girl.html}}</ref> An article from ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' declared that \"Dan and Blair together are like Harry Burns and Sally Albright reincarnated \u2014 the couple was obviously inspired by ''[[When Harry Met Sally...]]''.\" It further commented that the couple paralleled Pacey and Joey's relationship from ''[[Dawson's Creek]]'' and concluded that Dan and Blair were \"the most inspired storyline and couple of the show\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Alfonso |last=Espina |title=The End of Gossip Girl: Chair vs. Dair |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |page= |date=December 19, 2012 |accessdate=September 8, 2016 |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/alfonso-espina/gossip-girl-finale_b_2324665.html}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' stated that Dan and Blair were like stars in an \"updated version of ''[[You've Got Mail]]''\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Tim |last=Stack |title=Gossip Girl recap: Dair to Get Closer |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |page= |date=February 15, 2011 |accessdate=September 8, 2016 |url=http://www.ew.com/recap/gossip-girl-season-4-episode-15/2}}</ref> Tierney Bricker of [[E!]] ranked all 25 ''Gossip Girl'' couples placing 'Dair' as the third best couple after Blair and Serena (#1) and 'Chair' (#2). Bricker stated that \"[Dan and Blair], out of all the main characters, were the most well-suited for each other. In real life, they would've been 'endgame'.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Tierney |last=Bricker |title=We Ranked All the Gossip Girl Couples and No. 1 May Surprise You |work=[[E!]] |page= |date=November 28, 2015 |accessdate=September 8, 2016 |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/719091/we-ranked-all-the-gossip-girl-couples-and-no-1-may-surprise-you}}</ref>\n\nDawn Fallik of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' was less positive, asserting that \"both characters have been so Blandified that there's no fun left in the show.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Dawn |last=Fallik |title=''Gossip Girl'' Season 4, Episode 17 'Empire of the Son': TV Recap |work=The Wall Street Journal |page= |date=February 28, 2011 |accessdate=March 28, 2011 |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2011/02/28/gossip-girl-season-4-episode-17-empire-of-the-son-tv-recap/}}</ref> A writer for ''E! Online''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Team WWK labeled the Dan/Blair relationship \"nomance nonsense\".<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |title=Spoiler Chat: Get Sweeps Scoop on Your Fave Gossip Girl, Glee and Grey's Anatomy Couples |work=E! |page= |date=May 11, 2011 |accessdate=July 16, 2011 |url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/watch_with_kristin/b235864_spoiler_chat_get_sweeps_scoop_on_your.html}}</ref>\n\nWith regard to Chuck and Blair, Meester stated, \"I can really relate to it\u2014not necessarily because it's this dramatic, tumultuous relationship, but because the way they love each other is very real, and not for the sake of being dramatic. It's actual love. There's nobody for each other but them.\"<ref>{{cite news |first= Katy|last= Hall|title=Leighton Meester In ''Allure'' |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |page= |date=December 14, 2010 |accessdate=December 14, 2010 |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/12/14/leighton-meester-in-allur_n_796354.html}}</ref> Meester also expressed fondness for Dan and Blair, however, stating, \"I think they're good for each other in a lot of ways, in a way that Chuck and Blair aren't.\"<ref name=DB/> Badgley claimed that he thought \"Blair [was] Dan's soul mate\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Karlis |last=Nicole |title=Penn Badgley Reveals: 'Blair Is Dan's Soul Mate'! |work=[[Hollywoodlife.com]] |page= |date=October 14, 2011 |accessdate=September 8, 2016 |url=http://hollywoodlife.com/2011/10/14/penn-badgley-blair-waldorf-dan-humphry-soulmate-gossip-girl/}}</ref> and further stated that he thought the Blair and Dan storyline was \"the most exciting for Dan as a person\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Robyn |last=Ross |title=Gossip Girl's Leighton Meester: I Want the Blair and Dan Relationship to Play Out |work=[[TV Guide]] |page= |date=November 20, 2011 |accessdate=September 8, 2016 |url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/gossip-girl-leighton-meester-1039943/ }}</ref> When ''[[Hollywoodlife.com]]'' asked [[Ed Westwick]], who played Chuck Bass, which character he thought loved Blair more, Chuck or Dan, Westwick pointed to Badgley, saying \"definitely him.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Karlis |last=Nicole |title='Gossip Girl' Stars Ed Westick & Penn Badgley Reveal Who Loves Blair More |work=[[Hollywoodlife.com]] |page= |date=February 13, 2012 |accessdate=September 8, 2016 |url=http://hollywoodlife.com/2012/02/13/chuck-blair-dan-love-gossip-girl-season-5/}}</ref>\n\nProducers initially noticed chemistry between Blair and Dan in the {{nowrap|Season 1}} episode \"Bad News Blair\". According to producer Joshua Safran, the creators planned to revisit their relationship once the timing was right. Safran also stated that the outcome wasn't necessarily decided ahead of time. \"One thing we are very conscious of\u2014and I know some fans get upset about this\u2014is we really try to treat the characters as living, breathing, well-rounded individuals. And we're often surprised by where their journeys take them; they open new doors for us all the time,\" he said.<ref name=JS/>\n\n====Controversy====\nFollowing the {{nowrap|twentieth episode}} of {{nowrap|Season 4,}} Safran spoke on behalf of the series regarding the scene in which Chuck became violent with Blair.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Arrow |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'' Boss: \"Chuck Has Never, and Will Never, Hurt Blair\" |work=[[E!]] Online |page= |date=May 3, 2011 |accessdate=May 10, 2011 |url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/watch_with_kristin/b239902_gossip_girl_boss_chuck_has_never_will.html}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|The way we viewed it, I think it's very clear that Blair is not afraid in those moments, for herself. They have a volatile relationship, they always have, but I do not believe\u2014or I should say we do not believe\u2014that it is abuse when it's the two of them. Chuck does not try to hurt Blair. He punches the glass because he has rage, but he has never, and will never, hurt Blair. He knows it and she knows it, and I feel it's very important to know that she is not scared\u2014if anything, she is scared for Chuck\u2014and what he might do to himself, but she is never afraid of what he might do to her. Leighton and I were very clear about that.}}\n\nIn response to these comments, Carina MacKenzie of [[Zap2it]] stated, \"We're left wondering if Safran missed the part where she went home bleeding because Chuck was using physical intimidation to release his own emotions.\"<ref name=MacKenzie>{{cite news |first=Carina |last=MacKenzie |title=''Gossip Girl'': Is Chuck Bass abusive? E.P. says no; we beg to differ |work=Zap2it |date=May 3, 2011 |accessdate=May 10, 2011 |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/05/gossip-girl-is-chuck-bass-abusive-ep-says-no-we-beg-to-differ.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110507231323/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/05/gossip-girl-is-chuck-bass-abusive-ep-says-no-we-beg-to-differ.html |archivedate=May 7, 2011 }}</ref> While reviewing the episode, Tierney Bricker of Zap2it felt that there were \"really no excuses for Chuck Bass anymore.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Tierney |last=Bricker |title=Blair catches Royal Wedding fever |work=Zap2it |date=May 3, 2011 |accessdate=May 8, 2011 |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/05/gossip-girl-the-princesses-and-the-frog-blair-catches-royal-wedding-fever.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110507014356/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/05/gossip-girl-the-princesses-and-the-frog-blair-catches-royal-wedding-fever.html |archivedate=May 7, 2011 }}</ref> MacKenzie concluded that Chuck's behavior throughout {{nowrap|Season 4}} fit the signs of an [[Relational aggression|abusive relationship]], citing examples from ''HelpGuide.org'', a non-profit health resource. She noted Chuck's public humiliation of Blair, his attempt to pawn her during a business deal, and his use of physical intimidation. MacKenzie also called the show's explanation \"disturbing, particularly given the young, female target demographic of ''Gossip Girl'' and The CW.\"<ref name=MacKenzie/>\n\nIn a review for the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', Judy Berman addressed Safran's description of Blair during the scene. \"Considering how terrified Blair looked at the end of their encounter, and how quickly she got out of there, the show is sending a mixed message at best.\" She went on to state, \"We have no right to expect ''Gossip Girl'' to be a paragon of morality, or even realism, but the idea that true love requires taking a shard of glass to the face is disturbing even in this alternate, soap-opera dimension.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Judy |last=Berman |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'' recap: They tried to make Chuck go to rehab |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |page= |date=May 10, 2011 |accessdate=May 10, 2011 |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2011/05/gossip-girl-recap-they-tried-to-make-chuck-go-to-rehab.html}}</ref>\n\n===Season 5===\nIn the fifth-season premiere, Blair continues to plan her wedding, but begins to encounter problems in her relationship with Louis. It is later revealed that she is pregnant.<ref name=child/> Blair tells Chuck that the child is Louis', and states that part of her wanted Chuck to be the father.<ref>{{cite news |first=Dawn |last=Fallik |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'', Season 5, Episode 3, 'The Jewel of Denial': TV Recap |work=The Wall Street Journal |page= |date=October 10, 2011 |accessdate=October 11, 2011 |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2011/10/10/gossip-girl-season-5-episode-3-the-jewel-of-denial-tv-recap/?mod=google_news_blog}}</ref> Dan becomes Blair's confidante and is shown to be in love with her, though she remains oblivious to his feelings and states that there is nothing more than friendship between them.\n\nThough she insists that she is in love with Louis, Blair begins to seek Chuck out as the season progresses. The two eventually declare their love for each other prior to a car accident in her limousine while being chased by paparazzi. Though both recover, Blair suffers a miscarriage from the crash. After the crash Blair decides that she must commit herself to Louis, converting to [[Catholic Church|Catholicism]] and cutting off any connection with Chuck. At the wedding, Gossip Girl releases a recording of Blair confessing her love for Chuck. Nevertheless, Louis and Blair get married, making Blair a Princess of Monaco, though Louis informs her that they will have a loveless marriage of convenience.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |title= Gossip Girl's 100th Episode Shocker |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=January 30, 2012 |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2012/01/30/gossip-girl-blair-dan-wedding-100-episode/}}</ref> She then receives support from Dan, leading them to share a kiss on Valentine's Day. Amidst these developments, Blair grows conflicted between her feelings for Dan and Chuck.<ref>{{cite news |first=Laura |last=Prudom |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'' Recap: Dan And Blair Confront Their Feelings In 'Cross Rhodes' |work=Huffington Post |page= |date=February 21, 2012 |accessdate=February 22, 2012 |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/laura-prudom/gossip-girl-recap-cross-rhodes_b_1289931.html}}</ref> After taking steps to end her marriage, she chooses to begin a romantic relationship with Dan.<ref>{{cite news |first=Catriona |last=Wightman |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'': 'The Princess Dowry' recap |work=DigitalSpy.com |page= |date=February 28, 2012 |accessdate=March 3, 2012 |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/s83/gossip-girl/recaps/a368223/gossip-girl-the-princess-dowry-recap.html}}</ref> By the end of the season, however, after a debate about which love is the best\u2014with Dan she feels safe, with Chuck she feels vulnerable\u2014Blair declares that she is still in love with Chuck, and chooses to pursue him.<ref>{{cite news|first=Tierney |last=Bricker |title=''Gossip Girl'' Finale Redux: Blair Chooses Her Man! So What Comes Next? |work=E! |date=May 14, 2012 |accessdate=May 15, 2012 |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/watch_with_kristin/gossip_girl_finale_redux_blair_chooses/316189 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120516112642/http://www.eonline.com/news/watch_with_kristin/gossip_girl_finale_redux_blair_chooses/316189 |archivedate=May 16, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Season 6===\nIn the final season, Blair resumes her romantic relationship with Chuck, while Chuck and his father Bart\u2014who is revealed to be alive in the previous season\u2014become bitter rivals. Blair pursues her career as head of Waldorf Designs, with several mishaps, before staging a successful line.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wetpaint.com/gossip-girl-recap-of-season-7-episode-6-chuck-tells-blair-its-over-739230/ |title=Gossip Girl Recap of Season 6, Episode 7: Chuck Tells Blair It's Over |website=[[Wetpaint]] |date=November 27, 2012 |first=Whitney |last=Ricketts |accessdate=November 30, 2015}}</ref> In the penultimate episode, Bart falls to his death while trying to attack Chuck atop a building. Afterward, Blair and Chuck depart together. In the series finale, Blair marries Chuck which results in her not having to testify against him in his father's murder case. Five years later, Blair is shown to be running her mother's successful fashion line and she works with Jenny in a line called \"J for Waldorf\", and she and Chuck are shown to have a son named Henry.<ref>{{cite news |first=Dawn |last=Fallik |coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'', Season 6, Episode 9, 'The Revengers': TV Recap |work=E! |page= |date=December 10, 2012 |accessdate=December 13, 2012 |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2012/12/10/gossip-girl-season-6-episode-9-the-revengers-tv-recap/}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===In print===\nWhile covering the book series, Janet Malcolm of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' labeled the character \"an [[antihero]]ine of the first rank,\" and asserted that \"the series belongs to awful Blair, who inspires von Ziegesar's highest flights of comic fancy.\" She also compared Blair to vintage film and literary figures such as [[Becky Sharp (character)|Becky Sharp]] of ''[[Vanity Fair (novel)|Vanity Fair]]'', and Lizzie Eustace of ''[[The Eustace Diamonds]]''.<ref name=NYreview/> In addition, several critics have likened Blair to the character Lila Fowler of the earlier ''[[Sweet Valley High]]'' series.<ref name=fowler=one/><ref name=fowler-two/><ref>{{cite news |first=Michelle |last=Ruiz |coauthors= |title=The Long-Awaited ''Sweet Valley High'' Movie Is Happening at Last |work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] |page= |date=July 31, 2017 |accessdate=September 1, 2018 |url=https://www.vogue.com/article/sweet-valley-high-movie}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2007 book ''Children's Literature and Culture'', writer Harry Edwin Eiss chastised the depiction of Blair's bulimia. \"If handled properly, the inclusion of her illness could have provided a powerful lesson for young adult readers who worry about their weight and food consumption. Unfortunately, Cecily von Ziegesar, the author of the series, presents a seriously flawed treatment of the problem. In a failed attempt at humor, the writer regards Blair's sickness as just another source of gossip,\" he said.<ref>{{cite news |first=Harry |last=Eiss |coauthors= |title=''Children's Literature and Culture'' |work=Cambridge Scholars Publishing |page=133 |year=2007 |accessdate=July 12, 2011 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xqYpAQAAIAAJ&dq=Children%27s+literature+and+culture&q=blair+waldorf+bulimic}}</ref> Emily Nussbaum of ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine had similar comments, calling the bulimia \"more of an icky weakness than a full-fledged pathology.\" However, she went on to commend Blair as \"hilariously self-centered\".<ref name=nyarticle/>\n\nJulie Opipari of ''Manga Maniac Cafe'' gave the initial ''Gossip Girl'' manga a negative review, citing displeasure with the characters and plot. However, she acknowledged that this gave her a greater appreciation for Blair in the second volume, noting that Blair \"really had to learn how to rough it\" after losing her privileged lifestyle. She went on to state that \"Blair is one character that is fun to hate on. So imagine my surprise when I actually started to like her by the end of the book\".<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Review: Gossip Girl: For Your Eyes Only V 2 |work=Manga Maniac Cafe |page= |date=December 22, 2011 |accessdate=February 23, 2012 |url=http://www.mangamaniaccafe.com/?p=5824 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208115950/http://www.mangamaniaccafe.com/?p=5824 |archive-date=December 8, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===On screen===\n[[File:Leightonchanel.jpg|thumb|170px|right|alt=Leighton Meester in a black dress|Meester's portrayal of Blair has been met with critical acclaim. The actress prepared by reading ''Gossip Girl''.<ref name=ctv/>]]\nThe show's [[List of breakout characters|breakout character]],<ref>{{cite news |first=Ben |last=Widdicombe |coauthors= |title=A ''Gossip Girl'' dropout |work=Daily News (New York)|page= |date=April 9, 2008 |accessdate=October 3, 2009 |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/gossip/2008/04/09/2008-04-09_a_gossip_girl_dropout__or_did_leighton_m.html}}</ref> Blair Waldorf has garnered much media recognition. ''Yahoo!'' proclaims Blair a member of \"television's pantheon of razor-witted, solipsistic high school Alpha females.\"<ref name=YahooReview/> While commenting on Meester, ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine's 2008 cover story of the series states, \"Her villain-you-want-to-root-for is the most sophisticated performance on the show.\"<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=The Genius of ''Gossip Girl'' |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |page= |date= |accessdate=July 24, 2009 |url=http://nymag.com/arts/tv/features/46225/index4.html}}</ref> In another 2008 article, ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine commented that \"Meester has burst out of this ensemble to stardom.\"<ref name=pmag>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Leighton Meester |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |page= |date= |accessdate=October 9, 2008|url=http://www.people.com/people/leighton_meester}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' described her performance as similar to that of \"a predatory junior [[Joan Collins]] who practically breathes fire out of her pinched, perfectly WASP-ish nostrils.\"<ref name=pmag/> ''[[FHM]] Online'' ranked the actress the \"Hottest TV Star\" of autumn 2008, stating that as Blair Waldorf, \"Leighton Meester has stolen the spotlight with her mind-blowing good looks and amazing performance.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=''Gossip Girl'' Meester TV's Hottest star|work=[[Reuters]]|date=September 22, 2008|accessdate=October 30, 2011|url=http://blogs.reuters.com/fanfare/2008/09/22/gossip-girl-meester-tvs-hottest-star-kath-kim-a-bomb-fhm/|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080925053929/http://blogs.reuters.com/fanfare/2008/09/22/gossip-girl-meester-tvs-hottest-star-kath-kim-a-bomb-fhm/|archivedate=September 25, 2008}}</ref> ''[[OK!]]'' magazine likened her character to [[Audrey Hepburn]]'s portrayal of Holly Golightly.<ref name=OKmag>{{cite news|title=OK! Interview: Leighton Meester |work=[[OK!]] |date=September 18, 2008 |accessdate=October 4, 2009 |url=http://www.okmagazine.com/2008/09/ok-interview-leighton-meester-9072/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204132059/http://www.okmagazine.com/2008/09/ok-interview-leighton-meester-9072/ |archivedate=December 4, 2010 }}</ref> The physical similarity was also noted by ''[[USA Today]]''.<ref>{{cite news |first=Craig |last=Wilson |coauthors= |title=Here's A Toast To 'Tiffany's' On Landmark Novel's 50th Birthday |work=[[USA Today]] |page= |date=October 28, 2008 |accessdate=November 23, 2010 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/books/news/2008-10-28-tiffanys_N.htm}}</ref>\n\nIn its 2009 \"Hot List\", ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' cited Blair as \"the reason we love the back-stabby soap most.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Jason |last=Gay |title=Gossip Girl's Leighton Meester; our 2009 hot list leader |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=July 9, 2009 |url=http://music.ninemsn.com.au/blog.aspx?blogentryid=288940&showcomments=true |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929121654/http://music.ninemsn.com.au/blog.aspx?blogentryid=288940&showcomments=true |archivedate=September 29, 2011 }}</ref> Regarding the fictional fame of Blair's friend Serena, Tim Stack of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' asserted that \"Serena may be the star of the media but Blair is quickly becoming the star of this show.\"<ref>{{cite news |first= Tim|last= Stack|coauthors= |title=''Gossip Girl'': Yale and Hearty |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |page= |date= October 14, 2008|accessdate=February 22, 2009 |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20232869,00.html}}</ref> While citing Serena's long-revered allure, ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'' and its readers compared the two characters in 2008, with Blair being recognized as more beautiful than Serena.<ref>{{cite news |first= Petra|last= Guglielmetti|coauthors= |title=Who's Prettier: Blair or Serena? |work=[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]] |page= |date=October 14, 2008 |accessdate=July 5, 2009|url=http://www.glamour.com/beauty/blogs/girls-in-the-beauty-department/2008/10/whos-prettier-blair-or-serena.html}}</ref> In a review from ''[[The Atlantic]]'', Blair and Serena's friendship was praised as \"it offered a relationship whose depth and complexity approached [[Rory Gilmore and Paris Geller|Rory and Paris]]' [from ''[[Gilmore Girls]]''].\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Li|first1=Shirley|title=When Paris Met Rory: TV's Last Great Teenage-Girl Friendship|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2014/10/tvs-female-friendships-should-follow-rory-and-paris-lead-from-gilmore-girls/380957/|website=[[The Atlantic]]|accessdate=August 22, 2015|date=October 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, Blair received attention from ''[[Forbes]]'', which interviewed her via the series' writers.<ref>{{cite news |first= Anna|last= Broek|coauthors= |title=The Forbes Fictional Interview: Blair Waldorf |work=[[Forbes]] |page= |date=May 13, 2009 |accessdate=July 5, 2009|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/05/13/gossip-girl-interview-leadership-waldorf.html}}</ref> ''[[Television Without Pity]]'' listed Meester in their \"[[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globes]] 2009: Overlooked TV Shows and Performances\" article, labeling Blair \"so multi-faceted, well-dressed and beautifully played that she elevates this teen soap to something we don't even feel guilty about admitting we love.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Golden Globes 2009: Overlooked TV Shows and Performances |work=Television Without Pity |url=http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/show/golden_globes/golden_globes_2009_overlooked_1.php |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091223070026/http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/show/golden_globes/golden_globes_2009_overlooked_1.php |archivedate=2009-12-23 }}</ref> Meester won the [[Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Award]] for \"Choice TV Actress Drama\" in 2009,<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Teen Choice Award Winners |work=[[CBS]] |page= |date=August 10, 2009 |accessdate=August 26, 2009 |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/08/10/entertainment/main5229758.shtml}}</ref> and again in 2010.<ref>{{cite news |first=Natalie |last=Finn |coauthors= |title=Teens Deem Kardashians Choice Reality TV |work=[[E!]] |page= |date= August 8, 2010 |accessdate=August 9, 2010 |url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/b194308_teens_deem_kardashians_choice_reality_tv.html}}</ref> In 2009, she was voted the \"Best Mean Girl\" in Zap2it{{'s}} first poll of the best television characters in the 2000s.<ref>{{cite web|last=Grieser |first=Andy |title=The decade's best television characters, according to you |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2009/08/the-decades-best-television-characters-according-to-you.html |work=Zap2it |publisher=[[Tribune Media Services]] |accessdate=September 18, 2012 |date=August 25, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100918190838/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2009/08/the-decades-best-television-characters-according-to-you.html |archivedate=September 18, 2010 }}</ref> In February 2012, Zap2it held another poll to determine TV's Most Crushworthy. Blair was elected TV's Most Crushworthy 1% Female over [[Temperance \"Bones\" Brennan]].<ref>{{cite web|title=TV's Most Crushworthy 1% (Female) |url=http://www.zap2it.com/news/pictures/zap-tv-most-crushworthy-awards-pics,0,2089692.photogallery?index=21 |work=Zap2it |publisher=Tribune Media Services |accessdate=May 19, 2012 |author=MacKenzie, Carina Adly |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511051125/http://www.zap2it.com/news/pictures/zap-tv-most-crushworthy-awards-pics%2C0%2C2089692.photogallery?index=21 |archivedate=May 11, 2012 }}</ref> The 1 percenters are people that \"have everything going for them with their fantastic good looks and their opulent lifestyle\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Eckstein|first=David|title=TV's Most Crushworthy - The 1 percenters: 'Gossip Girl' stars Ed Westwick and Leighton Meester take on Emily Deschanel and Justin Hartley|url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2012/02/tvs-most-crushworthy---the-1-percenters-gossip-girl-stars-ed-westwick-and-leighton-meester-take-on-e.html|work=[[Zap2it]]|accessdate=May 19, 2012|date=February 23, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512052213/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2012/02/tvs-most-crushworthy---the-1-percenters-gossip-girl-stars-ed-westwick-and-leighton-meester-take-on-e.html|archivedate=May 12, 2012}}</ref> Her relationship with [[Chuck Bass]] was included in ''[[TV Guide]]''{{'s}} list of \"The Best TV Couples of All Time\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Couples Pictures, Gossip Girl Photos - Photo Gallery: The Best TV Couples of All Time |url=http://www.tvguide.com/PhotoGallery/Best-TV-Couples-1026715/1026739 |work=[[TV Guide]] |accessdate=June 20, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925233416/http://www.tvguide.com/PhotoGallery/Best-TV-Couples-1026715/1026739 |archivedate=September 25, 2012 }}</ref> as well as ''Entertainment Weekly''{{'s}} \"30 Best 'Will They/Won't They?' TV Couples\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bierly|first1=Mandi|last2=Fog|first2=Henning|title=30 Best 'Will They/Won't They?' TV Couples &#124; Photo 21 of 30|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20304425_21156349,00.html#20670143|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time Inc]]|accessdate=July 7, 2012|date=May 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe character's wardrobe\u2014credited to designers Abigail Lorick and Eric Daman<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Designers to Watch: Abigail Lorick |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |page= |date=August 29, 2008 |accessdate=October 30, 2011 |url=http://nymag.com/daily/fashion/2008/08/designer_abigail_lorick.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first= Margy|last= Rochlin|coauthors= |title=Eric Daman: ''Gossip Girl'' |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |page= |date=June 7, 2009|accessdate=July 5, 2009|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/07/arts/television/07dama.html}}</ref>\u2014was popular, earning mentions from periodicals such as ''[[InStyle]]''<ref name=instyle>{{cite news|title=''Gossip Girl'' Season One: Get the Look |work=[[InStyle]] |date=September 19, 2008 |accessdate=October 9, 2008 |url=http://www.instyle.com/instyle/package/general/photos/0,,20164507_20057738_20371760,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081019191151/http://www.instyle.com/instyle/package/general/photos/0%2C%2C20164507_20057738_20371760%2C00.html |archivedate=October 19, 2008 }}</ref> and ''New York'',<ref name=nymag>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Blair Waldorf's Wardrobe Does Not Go Home With Her |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |page= |date=March 19, 2008 |accessdate=October 9, 2008 |url=http://nymag.com/daily/fashion/2008/03/blair_waldorfs_wardrobe_does_n.html}}</ref> along with recognition from websites.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Blair Waldorf's Signature Looks |work=ctv.ca |page= |date= |accessdate=October 9, 2008 |url=http://www.ctv.ca/gallery/html/gg_blair_looks_071126/photo_0.html}}</ref> ''TV Guide'' listed Blair among its \"Best Dressed TV Characters of 2007\".<ref>{{cite news|title=The Best Dressed TV Characters of 2007 |work=[[TV Guide]] |date=Autumn 2007 |accessdate=October 30, 2011 |url=http://www.tvguide.com/PhotoGallery/Best-Dressed-TV-1680/2665 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120913013929/http://www.tvguide.com/PhotoGallery/Best-Dressed-TV-1680/2665 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-09-13 }}</ref> ''Entertainment Weekly'' named Blair Waldorf and Chuck Bass the \"Most Stylish\" characters of 2008.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=The Best & Worst of 2008 |work=Entertainment Weekly |page= |date= |accessdate=July 9, 2009|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20162677_20164091_20243883_9,00.html}}</ref> [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] television ranks Blair first in its listing of \"The Top 10 Best-Dressed TV Characters\",<ref>{{cite news|first=Melissa |last=Kagan |title=Top 10 Best-Dressed TV Characters |work=[[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] |accessdate=July 9, 2009 |url=http://www.mylifetime.com/lifestyle/beauty-style/celebrity-style/top-10-best-dressed-tv-characters#id=1 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090613070511/http://www.mylifetime.com/lifestyle/beauty-style/celebrity-style/top-10-best-dressed-tv-characters |archivedate=June 13, 2009 }}</ref> while ''Glamour'' has named her among its best-dressed TV characters of all time.<ref>{{cite news |first=Tracey |last=Lomrantz |coauthors= |title=Meet The 9 Best Dressed TV Characters Of All Time |work=Glamour |page= |date=September 26, 2008 |accessdate=July 9, 2009|url=http://www.glamour.com/fashion/blogs/slaves-to-fashion/2008/09/meet-the-9-best-dressed-tv-cha.html}}</ref> In a ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' interview, costume designers Eric Daman and Meredith Markworth-Pollack named Audrey Hepburn and ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' editor-in-chief [[Anna Wintour]] as their inspirations when dressing Meester as Blair. The designers also cited New York socialites [[Tinsley Mortimer]] and Arden Wohl as influences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/online/daily/2008/04/welcome-back-go.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110301202401/http://www.vanityfair.com/online/daily/2008/04/welcome-back-go.html |archivedate=March 1, 2011 |title=Welcome Back, Gossip Girl |work=Vanity Fair |date=March 17, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''TV Guide'' named her the sixth most fashionable TV character.<ref>{{cite web|title=Blair Waldorf Pictures - Photo Gallery: Who Are the Most Fashionable TV Characters? |url=http://www.tvguide.com/PhotoGallery/Fashionable-TV-Characters-1044392/1044402 |work=TV Guide |accessdate=September 14, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002014214/http://www.tvguide.com/PhotoGallery/Fashionable-TV-Characters-1044392/1044402 |archivedate=October 2, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n;Books\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last=von Ziegesar |first=Cecily |title=Gossip Girl: Because I'm Worth It |publisher=Poppy ([[Little, Brown and Company]]) |year=2003 |pages= |isbn=978-0-316-90968-6 |url=https://archive.org/details/becauseimworthit00vonz }}\n*{{cite book|last=von Ziegesar |first=Cecily |title=You Know You Love Me: A Gossip Girl Novel |url=https://archive.org/details/youknowyouloveme00litt |url-access=registration |publisher=Poppy (Little, Brown and Company) |year=2002 |pages= |isbn=978-0-316-91148-1}}\n*{{cite book |last=von Ziegesar |first=Cecily |title=Gossip Girl: I Will Always Love You |publisher=Poppy (Little, Brown and Company) |year=2009 |pages= |isbn=978-0-316-04361-8 |url=https://archive.org/details/gossipgirliwilla00ceci_0 }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{Gossip Girl}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Waldorf, Blair}}\n[[Category:Gossip Girl characters]]\n[[Category:Characters in American novels of the 21st century]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2002]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters from New York City]]\n[[Category:Fictional socialites]]\n[[Category:Fictional princesses]]\n[[Category:Fictional Monegasque people]]\n[[Category:Fictional bullies]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with body dysmorphia]]\n[[Category:Teenage characters in television]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with bulimia]]\n[[Category:Fictional Yale University people]]\n", "name_user": "2601:800:c004:3e80:d4b2:2c2c:a847:899a", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(I added some names that were more accurate to what the revelation series portrayed.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blair_Waldorf"}
{"title_page": "The Last O.G.", "text_new": "{{short description|American comedy television series}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = The Last O.G.\n| image                = TheLastOGTV.png\n| image_size           = 265px\n| caption              = Title screen from the pilot\n| genre                = [[Television comedy|Comedy]]\n| creator              = {{Plainlist|\n* John Carcieri\n* [[Jordan Peele]]\n}}\n| starring             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Tracy Morgan]]\n* [[Tiffany Haddish]]\n* [[Allen Maldonado]]\n* [[Ryan Gaul]]\n* Taylor Christian Mosby\n* Dante Hoagland\n* [[Cedric the Entertainer]]\n}}\n| theme_music_composer =\n| opentheme            =\n| composer             = [[Joseph Stephens]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons          = 3\n| num_episodes         = 23\n| list_episodes        = #Episodes\n| executive_producer   = {{Plainlist|\n* Tracy Morgan\n* [[Jorma Taccone]]\n* Eric Tannenbaum\n* Kim Tannenbaum\n* Joel Zadak\n* John Carcieri\n* Jordan Peele\n}}\n| producer             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Alex Rubens]]\n* Jason Wang\n* Steven Ast\n}}\n| editor               =\n| location             = [[New York City]]\n| cinematography       = Michael Simmonds\n| camera               = [[Single-camera setup|Single-camera]]\n| runtime              = 22 minutes\n| company              = {{Plainlist|\n* Streetlife Productions Inc.\n* [[Monkeypaw Productions]]\n* Full Flavor\n* The Tannenbaum Company\n* {{nowrap|Principato-Young Entertainment}}\n* Matthew 633\n* Artists First\n* Studio T\n}}\n| distributor          = [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n| network              = [[TBS (U.S. TV channel)|TBS]]\n| picture_format       =\n| audio_format         =\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2018|3|31}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|present}}\n| website              = http://www.tbs.com/shows/the-last-og\n| website_title        = Official website\n}}\n'''''The Last O.G.''''' is an American [[Television comedy|comedy]] television series created by [[Jordan Peele]] and John Carcieri that premiered on March 31, 2018, on [[TBS (U.S. TV channel)|TBS]]. The series follows a convict released after serving fifteen years who returns to [[Brooklyn]] to find his old neighborhood has changed, and his ex-girlfriend is raising their children with another man. It stars [[Tracy Morgan]], [[Tiffany Haddish]], [[Allen Maldonado]], [[Ryan Gaul]], Taylor Christian Mosby, Dante Hoagland, and [[Cedric the Entertainer]]. In April 2018, it was announced that the series had been renewed for a second season, which premiered on April 2, 2019. In May 2019, the series was renewed for a third season which premiered on April 7, 2020.<ref name=\"Season 3 Renewal\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/the-last-o-g-tracy-morgan-tiffany-haddish-renewed-season-3-tbs-1202615223/|title='The Last O.G.' Starring Tracy Morgan & Tiffany Haddish Renewed For Season 3 By TBS|work=Deadline Hollywood|first=Denise|last=Petski|date=May 15, 2019|accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Season 3 Premiere Date\"/>\n\n==Premise==\nTray is an ex-con who is released from prison for good behavior after serving fifteen years. He returns to his old Brooklyn neighborhood to find that it has become [[Gentrification|gentrified]]. His ex-girlfriend, Shannon (also known by nickname Shay-Shay), is now married to another man named Josh and is raising his twin children Amira and Shahzad. Tray decides to become a better man and a father with the help of the owner of a [[Halfway house|halfway house]], Mullins, and his cousin Bobby.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n===Main===\n* [[Tracy Morgan]] as Tray Barker\n* [[Tiffany Haddish]] as Shannon \"Shay-Shay\" Birkeland\n* [[Allen Maldonado]] as Bobby Barker\n** Maldonado also plays Clyde Barker, Bobby's deceased older brother\n* [[Ryan Gaul]] as Josh Birkeland\n* Taylor Christian Mosby as Amira Birkeland\n* Dante Hoagland as Shahzad Birkeland\n* [[Cedric the Entertainer]] as Miniard Mullins (Main Season 1, Recurring Season 2)\n\n===Recurring===\n* Joel Marsh Garland as Big Country\n* Gino Vento as Gustavo\n* Derek Gaines as Jason \"Jaybird\" Watkins\n* Daniel J. Watts as Felony\n* Dimitri Joseph Moise as Mostel Defferies\n* [[Malik Yoba]] as Wavy\n* [[Edi Patterson]] as Elizabeth\n* Miles G. Jackson as Benjamin\n* Natalie Carter as Ruth\n* Byrne Davis, Jr. as Billy C.\n* [[Randy Gambill]] as Jason\n* [[Bresha Webb]] as Faith\n* [[Method Man]] as Green-Eyes\n\n===Guest===\n* Jon J. Masters as Mr. Washington\n* [[Judith Roberts (actress)|Judith Roberts]] as Mrs. Washington\n* [[Chrissy Metz]] as Pooh Cat\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Series overview\n| color1     = #E3C0BE\n| link1      = #Season 1 (2018)\n| episodes1  = 10\n| start1     = {{Start date|2018|3|31}}\n| end1       = {{End date|2018|6|5}}\n\n| color2     = #2E516C\n| link2      = #Season 2 (2019)\n| episodes2  = 10\n| start2     = {{Start date|2019|3|30}}\n| end2       = {{End date|2019|6|4}}\n\n| color3     = #02D2BA\n| link3      = #Season 3 (2020)\n| episodes3  = \n| start3     = {{Start date|2020|4|7}}\n| end3       =\n}}\n\n===Season 1 (2018)===\n{{Episode table |background=#E3C0BE |overall= |season= |title=25 |director= |writer= |airdate= |viewers=10 |country=U.S. |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n |Title           = Pilot\n |DirectedBy      = [[Jorma Taccone]]\n |WrittenBy       =  John Carcieri & [[Jordan Peele]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|3|31}}{{efn|name=fn1|The episode originally aired as a \"sneak peek\" on March 31, 2018. It was later re-aired for its official television premiere on April 3, 2018.}}\n |Viewers         = 1.87<ref>{{cite news|last1=Porter|first1=Rick|title=Saturday cable ratings: Final Four scores for TBS, up from 2016|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/saturday-cable-ratings-march-31-2018/|accessdate=April 3, 2018|work=[[TV by the Numbers]]|date=April 3, 2018|language